'''Brian Hugh Warner''' (born January 5, 1969), known professionally as '''Marilyn Manson''', is an American singer, songwriter, actor, painter,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.101exhibit.com/exhibitions/marilyn-manson_1 |title=Marilyn Manson |website=101 Exhibit |date=November 4, 2008 |access-date=October 5, 2020 |archive-date=November 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201107223435/http://www.101exhibit.com/exhibitions/marilyn-manson_1 |url-status=live }}</ref> and writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genreisdead.com/book-review-marilyn-manson-by-perou/|title=Book Review: Marilyn Manson By Perou: 21 Years In Hell|website=Genre Is Dead|last=Perez Hollingsworth|first=Ashley|date=June 16, 2020|access-date=October 5, 2020|archive-date=September 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200926103944/https://genreisdead.com/book-review-marilyn-manson-by-perou/|url-status=live}}</ref> He is known for his controversial stage personality and image as the lead singer of [[Marilyn Manson (band)|the band of the same name]], which he co-founded with guitarist [[Scott Putesky|Daisy Berkowitz]] in 1989 and of which he remains the only constant member. Like the other founding members of the band, his [[stage name]] was formed by combining and juxtaposing the names of two opposing American cultural icons: a [[sex symbol]] and an infamous criminal; in Manson's case, actress [[Marilyn Monroe]] and [[cult]] leader [[Charles Manson]].

Manson is best known for music released in the 1990s, including the albums ''[[Portrait of an American Family]]'' (1994), ''[[Antichrist Superstar]]'' (1996) and ''[[Mechanical Animals]]'' (1998), which earned him a reputation in mainstream media as a controversial figure and negative influence on young people when combined with his public image.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marilyn Manson Concert Canceled |first=Glasgow |last=Greg |url=http://www.thedailycamera.com/shooting/23manson.html |format=[[Broadsheet]] |agency=[[MediaNews Group]] |newspaper=[[Camera (newspaper)|The Daily Camera]]  |date=April 23, 1999 |access-date=May 31, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060524090531/http://www.thedailycamera.com/shooting/23manson.html |archive-date=May 24, 2006 }}</ref><ref>Cullen, Dave. [http://www.salon.com/news/feature/1999/09/23/columbine/index.html Inside the Columbine High investigation] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126133759/http://www.salon.com/news/feature/1999/09/23/columbine/index.html |date=January 26, 2009 }}. ''Salon News'', September 23, 1999.</ref> In the U.S. alone, three of the band's albums have been awarded [[music recording sales certification#Certification thresholds|platinum]] status and three more went gold, and the band has had eight releases debut in the top 10, including two No. 1 albums. Manson has been ranked at No. 44 on the list of the "Top 100 Heavy Metal Vocalists" by ''[[Hit Parader]]'' and, along with his band, has been nominated for four [[Grammy Awards]]–Manson himself earned an additional Grammy nomination for his work on [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[Donda]]''. Manson made his film debut as an actor in [[David Lynch]]'s ''[[Lost Highway (1997 film)|Lost Highway]]'' (1997), and has since appeared in a variety of minor roles and cameos. In 2002, his first art show, ''The Golden Age of Grotesque'', was held at the [[Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions]] center.

He is widely considered one of the most controversial figures in [[heavy metal music]], and has been involved in numerous controversies throughout his career. His lyrics were criticized by American politicians and were examined in [[congressional hearing]]s. Several U.S. states enacted legislation specifically banning the group from performing in state-operated venues. In 1999, news media [[Marilyn Manson–Columbine High School massacre controversy|falsely blamed Manson for influencing the perpetrators of the Columbine High School massacre]]. His work has been cited in several other violent events; his paintings and films appeared as evidence in a [[Murder of Jodi Jones|murder trial]], and he has been accused of inspiring several other murders and school shootings. In 2021, multiple women accused Manson of psychologically and sexually abusing them, allegations he denied.<ref name="BB Timeline"/>

== Early life ==
Brian Hugh Warner was born in [[Canton, Ohio]], on January 5, 1969,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/01/05/UPI-Almanac-for-Saturday-Jan-5-2019/9081546481545/ |title= UPI Almanac for Saturday, Jan. 5, 2019|work=[[United Press International]]|date=January 5, 2019|access-date=September 6, 2019|archive-date=January 5, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190105134420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/01/05/UPI-Almanac-for-Saturday-Jan-5-2019/9081546481545/|url-status=live}}</ref> the only son of Barbara Warner Wyer (died May 13, 2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-mansons-mother-dies-after-battle-with-dementia/ |title=Marilyn Manson's Mother Dies After Battle With Dementia |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=May 18, 2014 |access-date=January 16, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233721/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-mansons-mother-dies-after-battle-with-dementia/ |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Hugh Angus Warner (died July 7, 2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://birth-records.mooseroots.com/l/10042596/Brian-Hugh-Warner|title=Brian Hugh Warner (b. 1969)|publisher=MooseRoots.com|access-date=March 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/hugh_warner_dies |title=Marilyn Manson shares heartfelt words after father's death |work=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=July 8, 2017 |access-date=July 9, 2017 |archive-date=September 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905023901/http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/hugh_warner_dies |url-status=live }}</ref> Of English, German, and Irish descent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/other/warnerbh.html |title=Ancestry of Marilyn Manson |publisher=Wargs.com |access-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202020011/http://wargs.com/other/warnerbh.html |archive-date=December 2, 2010 }}</ref> he has also claimed that his mother, whose family hailed from the [[Appalachian Mountains]] in [[West Virginia]], had [[Sioux]] heritage.<ref name="martyr">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/see-marilyn-manson-play-native-american-hit-man-in-movie-trailer-20150812 |title=See Marilyn Manson Play Native American Hit Man in Movie Trailer |date=August 12, 2015 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |access-date=August 13, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813024326/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/see-marilyn-manson-play-native-american-hit-man-in-movie-trailer-20150812 |archive-date=August 13, 2015 }}</ref> As a child, Warner attended his mother's [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal]] church, though his father was a [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beliefnet.com/Entertainment/Music/2001/05/Manson-Interview.aspx?p=2 |title=Marilyn Manson: The Beliefnet Interview |publisher=Beliefnet.com |first=Anthony |last=DeCurtis |access-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606173456/http://www.beliefnet.com/Entertainment/Music/2001/05/Manson-Interview.aspx?p=2 |archive-date=June 6, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/1997/072497/cover.html |title=Marilyn Manson |date=July 24, 1997 |work=Montreal Mirror |access-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063711/http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/1997/072497/cover.html |archive-date=June 6, 2011 }}</ref>

He attended [[Heritage Christian School (Canton, Ohio)|Heritage Christian School]] from first to tenth grade. In that school, his instructors tried to show children what music they were not supposed to listen to; Warner then fell in love with what he "wasn't supposed to."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allwomenstalk.com/7-facts-on-marilyn-manson/4/ |title=4. Christian School |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201111444/http://allwomenstalk.com/7-facts-on-marilyn-manson/4/ |archive-date=February 1, 2015 |date=April 4, 2011 }}</ref> Warner later transferred to [[GlenOak High School]] and graduated from there in 1987. After relocating with his parents, he became a student at [[Broward College|Broward Community College]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], in 1990. He was working towards a degree in [[journalism]], gaining experience in the field by writing articles for the music magazine ''[[25th Parallel (magazine)|25th Parallel]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spookykids.net/articles/25thparallel/|title=25th Parallel|publisher=Spookykids.net|access-date=January 10, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118080051/http://www.spookykids.net/articles/25thparallel/|archive-date=January 18, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> He also interviewed musicians and soon met several of the musicians to whom his own work was later compared, including [[Groovie Mann]] from [[My Life with the Thrill Kill Kult]] and [[Trent Reznor]] of [[Nine Inch Nails]], with the latter later becoming his mentor and producing his debut album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://folioweekly.com/THRILL-KILL-KULTS-MUSIC-TO-DANCE-SLAY-BY,9957 |title=THRILL KILL'S MUSIC TO DANCE, SLAY BY – Meet the guy who freaked out Marilyn Manson |last=Harper |first=Janet |date=June 4, 2014 |work=Folio Weekly |access-date=January 1, 2018 |archive-date=January 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101194547/http://folioweekly.com/THRILL-KILL-KULTS-MUSIC-TO-DANCE-SLAY-BY,9957 |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Career ==
=== Music ===
{{Main|Marilyn Manson (band)}}
The band was formed in 1989 by Warner and guitarist [[Scott Putesky]],{{sfn|Manson|Strauss|1998|pp=64–65}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://popmatters.com/article/interview-with-your-vampire-marilyn-manson/ |title=Interview with your vampire: Marilyn Manson|author=Hamersly, Michael|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=February 4, 2008|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614182452/http://www.popmatters.com/article/interview-with-your-vampire-marilyn-manson/|archive-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> with Warner writing lyrics and Putesky composing the majority of music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/daisy-berkowitz-marilyn-manson-scott-putesky-interview-1|title=Daisy Berkowitz: Portrait of an American Ex-Marilyn Manson Member|author=Tron, Gina|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=April 10, 2014|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402020101/http://noisey.vice.com/blog/daisy-berkowitz-marilyn-manson-scott-putesky-interview-1|archive-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Warner adopted the stage name Marilyn Manson and, alongside a revolving lineup of musicians, recorded the band's first demo tape as [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson & the Spooky Kids]] in 1990.{{sfn|Manson|Strauss|1998|pp=84, 90}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/manson-the-florida-years/Content?oid=1471906|title=Manson: The Florida Years|author=Kissell, Ted B |work=[[Cleveland Scene]]|publisher=Euclid Media Group|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809055236/http://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/manson-the-florida-years/Content?oid=1471906|archive-date=August 9, 2016}}</ref> The group quickly developed a loyal [[fanbase]] within the [[South Florida punk and hardcore]] music scene, primarily as a result of their intentionally [[shock value|shocking]] concerts; band members often performed in women's clothing or bizarre costumes, and live shows routinely featured amateur [[pyrotechnics]], naked women nailed to [[crucifix]]es, children locked in cages,<ref name="values">{{cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/music/manson-family-values-6362125|title=Manson Family Values|author=Baker, Greg|work=[[Miami New Times]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=July 20, 1994|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504022956/http://www.miaminewtimes.com/music/manson-family-values-6362125|archive-date=May 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=102639|title=Sunday Old School: Marilyn Manson|author=Diamond, Ollie H.|work=Metal Underground|date=May 11, 2014 |access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605100915/http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=102639 |archive-date=June 5, 2016}}</ref> as well as experiments in [[reverse psychology]] and butchered animals remains.{{#tag:ref|"In an attempt to reiterate the lesson of ''[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory|Willy Wonka]]'' in my own style during shows, I hung a donkey [[piñata]] over the crowd and put a stick on the edge of the stage. Then I would warn, 'Please, don't break that open. I beg you not to.' Human psychology being what it is, kids in the crowd would invariably grab the stick and smash the piñata apart, forcing everyone to suffer the consequence, which would be a shower of cow brains, chicken livers and pig intestines from [the] disemboweled donkey."{{sfn||Manson|Strauss|1998|pp=93–94}}|group=N}} Within six months of forming, they were playing sold-out shows in 300-capacity nightclubs throughout Florida.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/news/manson-family-feud-6318671|title=Manson Family Feud|author=Stratton, Jeff|work=[[New Times Broward-Palm Beach]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=April 15, 2004 |access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009152737/http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/news/manson-family-feud-6318671|archive-date=October 9, 2016}}</ref> They signed a [[recording contract|record deal]] with [[Sony Music]] in early 1991, although this deal was rescinded before any material was recorded for the label. The band instead used the proceeds of this deal to fund the recording of subsequent demo tapes, which were released independently.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2009-08-09/features/0908060176_1_lunchbox-marilyn-manson-brian-warner|author=Putesky, Scott|author-link=Scott Putesky|title=When Marilyn Manson Left His Kids Behind|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=August 9, 2009|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122235048/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2009-08-09/features/0908060176_1_lunchbox-marilyn-manson-brian-warner|archive-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref>

[[File:Nights of Nothing MM.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Left to right: Twiggy, Gacy and Manson performing at the "A Night of Nothing" industry showcase, 1995]]
The name of the group was shortened to Marilyn Manson in 1992, and they continued to perform and release cassettes until the summer of 1993,<ref name="values"/> when Reznor signed the act to his [[vanity label]] [[Nothing Records]].<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/marilyn-manson-mn0000825251/biography|title=Marilyn Manson – Biography & History|author=Ankeny, Jason|work=[[AllMusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426172735/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/marilyn-manson-mn0000825251/biography|archive-date=April 26, 2015}}</ref> Their debut studio album, ''[[Portrait of an American Family]]'', was released in July 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-portrait-of-an-american-family-album-anniversary/|title=26 Years Ago: Marilyn Manson Issues 'Portrait of an American Family'|author=Wiederhorn, Jon|work=[[Loudwire]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501054342/http://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-portrait-of-an-american-family-album-anniversary/|archive-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref> Manson later criticized Nothing Records and its parent label [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] for a perceived lack of promotion.{{#tag:ref|"Well, there was always a real chip on our shoulder that [''Portrait of an American Family''] never really got the push from the record label that we thought it deserved. It was all about us touring our fucking asses off. We toured for two years solid, [[Self Destruct Tour|opening]] up for Nine Inch Nails for a year and then doing [[Portrait of an American Family (tour)|our own club tours]]. It was all just about perseverance."{{sfn|Manson|Strauss|1998|pp=150–151}}|group=N}} While recording b-sides and remixes for the album's proposed third single, "[[Dope Hat]]", the band decided to issue the resultant material as a standalone release titled ''[[Smells Like Children]]''.{{sfn|Manson|Strauss|1998|pp=190–191}} The record included their cover version of the [[Eurythmics]]'s "[[Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)#Marilyn Manson cover|Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)]]", which established the band as a mainstream act.<ref name="allmusic"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123|title=Marilyn Manson: Sympathy for the Devil|author=Strauss, Neil|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 23, 1997|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423144646/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123|archive-date=April 23, 2017}}</ref> The song's music video was placed on heavy rotation on [[MTV]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/marilyn-manson-504532 |title=Marilyn Manson Biography|work=[[Biography.com]]|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404105149/http://www.biography.com/people/marilyn-manson-504532|archive-date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> and earned the band their first nomination for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Rock Video|Best Rock Video]] at the [[1996 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-09-04/features/1996248067_1_alanis-morissette-bone-thugs-n-harmony-tha-crossroads|title=Video Music Awards offer stars and unpredictability|author=Considine, J.D.|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=September 4, 1996|access-date=February 12, 2022}}</ref> Their second studio album, 1996's ''[[Antichrist Superstar]]'', sparked a fierce backlash among [[Christian fundamentalism|Christian fundamentalists]].<ref name=la1>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/mar/12/entertainment/ca-16387|title='Mechanical' Reaction|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Boehm, Mike|date=March 12, 1999 |access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406002923/http://articles.latimes.com/1999/mar/12/entertainment/ca-16387|archive-date=April 6, 2014}}</ref> The album was an immediate commercial success, debuting at number three on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and selling almost 2 million copies in the United States alone,<ref name="golden">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/manson-golden-at-number-one-20030521|title=Manson Golden at Number One|author=Dansby, Andrew|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=March 21, 2003|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320155738/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/manson-golden-at-number-one-20030521 |archive-date=March 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/951479/marilyn-manson-plots-2011-comeback-with-indie-label |title=Marilyn Manson Plots 2011 Comeback with Indie Label|author=Paine, Andre|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 8, 2010|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505052423/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/951479/marilyn-manson-plots-2011-comeback-with-indie-label|archive-date=May 5, 2016}}</ref> and 7 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocweekly.com/music/marilyn-mansons-antichrist-superstar-turns-15-as-born-villain-readies-for-release-6573973|title=Marilyn Manson's 'Antichrist Superstar' Turns 15 as 'Born Villain' Readies for Release|author=San Roman, Gabriel|work=[[OC Weekly]]|date=October 7, 2011|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113005555/http://www.ocweekly.com/music/marilyn-mansons-antichrist-superstar-turns-15-as-born-villain-readies-for-release-6573973|archive-date=January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/record-store-day-2016-the-full-list-of-557-exclusive-music-releases-revealed__14096/ |title=Record Store Day 2016: The full list of 557 exclusive music releases revealed|author=Copsey, Rob|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=March 8, 2016|access-date=March 1, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611040513/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/record-store-day-2016-the-full-list-of-557-exclusive-music-releases-revealed__14096/ |archive-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> Lead single "[[The Beautiful People (song)|The Beautiful People]]" received three nominations at the [[1997 MTV Video Music Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/34895/jamiroquai-tops-mtv-video-music-nom-list|title=Jamiroquai Tops MTV Video Music Nom List|author=Jolson-Colburn, Jeffrey|work=[[E! Online]]|publisher=[[E!]]|date=July 23, 1997|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425122635/http://www.eonline.com/news/34895/jamiroquai-tops-mtv-video-music-nom-list|archive-date=April 25, 2017}}</ref> where the band also performed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_au/article/ywzg7y/a-brief-history-of-marilyn-manson-pissing-off-jesus-christ |title=A Brief History of Marilyn Manson Pissing Off Jesus Christ|author=Sori, Alexandra|work=[[Noisey]]|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|date=June 3, 2017|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127122650/https://noisey.vice.com/en_au/article/ywzg7y/a-brief-history-of-marilyn-manson-pissing-off-jesus-christ|archive-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref>

For 1998's ''[[Mechanical Animals]]'', Manson said he took inspiration from 1970s [[glam rock]], and adopted a wardrobe and hairstyle similar to [[David Bowie]].<ref name="tide">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/aug/16/entertainment/ca-13559|title=Marilyn Manson Aims to Change Tide of the Mainstream|author=Hochman, Steve|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 16, 1998|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518010014/http://articles.latimes.com/1998/aug/16/entertainment/ca-13559|archive-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref> He said he did this to avoid being portrayed as a "[[bogeyman]]", a role which had been ascribed to him by mainstream media following the band's commercial breakthrough.<ref name=la1/> Interscope's promotion of the album was massive,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/501687/marilyn-manson-fans-queue-up-for-mechanical-animals/|title=Marilyn Manson Fans Queue Up For Mechanical Animals|author=Vanhorn, Teri|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]]|date=September 15, 1998|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610105950/http://www.mtv.com/news/501687/marilyn-manson-fans-queue-up-for-mechanical-animals/|archive-date=June 10, 2016}}</ref> with the label erecting enormous billboards of Manson as an [[Androgyny|androgynous]] [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] in [[Times Square]] and the [[Sunset Strip]].<ref name="tide"/> Lead single "[[The Dope Show]]" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]] at the [[41st Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name="Grammys">{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/20_artists_you_may_not_have_known_were_nominated_for_and_won_grammy_awards|title=20 artists you may not have known were nominated for (and won) Grammy Awards|author=McKinstry, Lee|work=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]|date=February 6, 2015|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221034304/http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/20_artists_you_may_not_have_known_were_nominated_for_and_won_grammy_awards|archive-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref> The album debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-manson-shows-hes-dope-19980924 |title=Marilyn Manson Shows He's Dope|author=Boehlert, Eric|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=September 24, 1998|access-date=March 14, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417030841/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-manson-shows-hes-dope-19980924|archive-date=April 17, 2015}}</ref> but was the [[List of Billboard 200 number-one albums of 1998|lowest-selling number-one album of 1998]] in the United States,<ref name="turkey">{{cite web |last=Grein |first=Paul |url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/20401/chart-watch-extra-what-a-turkey-the-25-worst-selling-1-albums/|title=Chart Watch Extra: What A Turkey! The 25 Worst-Selling #1 Albums|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=November 21, 2008|access-date=March 14, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926053208/http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/20401/chart-watch-extra-what-a-turkey-the-25-worst-selling-1-albums|archive-date=September 26, 2009}}</ref> with sales of 1.4 million copies in the country as of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-columbine-massacre-destroyed-career/|title=Marilyn Manson: Columbine Blame 'Destroyed My Career'|author=Hartmann, Graham|work=[[Loudwire]]|date=September 22, 2017|access-date=March 14, 2022}}</ref> The album was not well received by longtime fans, who complained about its radio-friendly sound and accused the vocalist of "[[sell out|selling out]]",<ref>{{cite web |last=Burk |first=Greg |url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/marilyn-a-re-examination-2132874|title=Marilyn: A Re-Examination|work=[[LA Weekly]]|date=January 10, 2001|access-date=March 14, 2022}}</ref> and Interscope were reportedly disappointed with its commercial performance.{{#tag:ref|[[Michael Beinhorn]], the co-producer of ''Mechanical Animals'', said: "When ''Mechanical Animals'' came out, the projected sales figure for the first week was 300,000 copies. [The label was] excited, saying, 'We're going to hit No.1 and sell 300k!'. It sold 230,000 and got to No.1, but it wasn't enough. The label lost interest, they took down the huge billboard they had in Times Square for the album, the president of the label called Manson up, screaming at him for having tits on the cover. I think that, and what happened at [[Marilyn Manson–Columbine High School massacre controversy|Columbine]], which really affected him emotionally, meant that he never made an album up to the standard of ''Mechanical Animals'' or ''Antichrist Superstar'' again. He just didn't get the support."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/marilyn-manson-vs-courtney-love-the-true-story-of-1999s-beautiful-monsters-tour|title=Marilyn Manson vs Courtney Love: The true story of 1999's Beautiful Monsters Tour|author=Hill, Stephen|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|date=August 2, 2019|access-date=February 12, 2022}}</ref> |group=N}}

''[[Holy Wood (In the Shadow of the Valley of Death)]]'' was a return to the band's [[industrial metal]] roots after the glam-influenced ''Mechanical Animals'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revolvermag.com/music/see-marilyn-manson-play-disposable-teens-mtv-new-years-eve-bash-2000|title=See Marilyn Manson Play 'Disposable Teens' on MTV New Years Eve Bash in 2000|work=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]|date=November 14, 2019|access-date=February 12, 2022}}</ref> and was the vocalist's response to media coverage blaming him for influencing [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold|the perpetrators]] of the [[Columbine High School massacre]]. The album was a critical success, with numerous publications praising it as the band's finest work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/columbine-how-marilyn-manson-became-mainstream-medias-scapegoat|title=Columbine: How Marilyn Manson Became Mainstream Media's Scapegoat|author=Brannigan, Paul|work=[[Kerrang!]]|date=April 20, 2020|access-date=February 12, 2022}}</ref> Despite being certified gold in the United States for shipments in excess of half a million units,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/manson-holy-wood-album-anniversary/|title=20 Years Ago: Marilyn Manson Releases 'Holy Wood' Album|author=Childers, Chad|work=[[Loudwire]]|date=November 14, 2019|access-date=February 12, 2022}}</ref> mainstream media openly questioned the band's commercial appeal, noting the dominance of [[nu metal]] and controversial [[hip hop artist]]s such as [[Eminem]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/20/entertainment/ca-54571/2 |title=Marilyn Manson May Be in for a Shock |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 20, 2000 |access-date=May 15, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306180317/http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/20/entertainment/ca-54571/2 |archive-date=March 6, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://teamrock.com/feature/2016-07-28/marilyn-manson-story-behind-holy-wood|title=Marilyn Manson: The Story Of Holy Wood (In The Shadow Of The Valley Of Death)|author=Udo, Tommy|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|date=July 28, 2016|access-date=February 12, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404201940/http://teamrock.com/feature/2016-07-28/marilyn-manson-story-behind-holy-wood|archive-date=April 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A cover of "[[Tainted Love#Marilyn Manson version (2001)|Tainted Love]]" was an international hit in 2002, peaking at number one in several territories.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hBEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14|title=Missing Tracks Mean Fewer U.S. Album Sales|author=Promis, Jose|date=September 27, 2003|access-date=February 12, 2022|magazine=Billboard|issn=0006-2510|volume=115|issue=39|page=14}}</ref>

''[[The Golden Age of Grotesque]]'' was released the following year, an album primarily inspired by the [[Swing music|swing]] and [[burlesque]] movements of [[1920s Berlin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dita-von-teese-on-remaining-friends-with-marilyn-manson-he-encouraged-all-of-my-eccentricities-a6950411.html|title=Dita Von Teese on remaining friends with Marilyn Manson: 'He encouraged all of my eccentricities'|author=Saul, Heather|work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 24, 2016|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510094803/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/dita-von-teese-on-remaining-friends-with-marilyn-manson-he-encouraged-all-of-my-eccentricities-a6950411.html|archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> In an [[extended metaphor]] found throughout the record, Manson compared his own often-criticized work to the ''[[Degenerate art|Entartete Kunst]]'' banned by the [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] regime.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://derstandard.at/1289559/Marilyn-Manson-ueber-Stimmung-in-USA-und-Entartete-Kunst|title=Marilyn Manson über Stimmung in USA und 'Entartete Kunst'|language=de|trans-title="Marilyn Manson on the mood in the US and 'Degenerate Art'"|work=[[Der Standard]]|date=May 5, 2003|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701173847/http://derstandard.at/1289559/Marilyn-Manson-ueber-Stimmung-in-USA-und-Entartete-Kunst |archive-date=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Like ''Mechanical Animals'' in 1998, ''The Golden Age of Grotesque'' debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200,<ref name="golden"/> but was the lowest-selling studio album to debut at number one that year, selling 527,000 copies in the United States as of 2008.<ref name="turkey"/> The album was more successful in Europe, where it sold over 400,000 on its first week of release to debut at number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[European Top 100 Albums]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/70899/kelly-timberlake-continue-uk-chart-reign|title=Kelly, Timberlake Continue U.K. Chart Reign |author=Sexton, Paul|magazine=Billboard|date=May 26, 2003|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118165145/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/70899/kelly-timberlake-continue-uk-chart-reign|archive-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Manson began his collaboration with French fashion designer [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]] during this period, who designed much of the elaborate attire worn by the band on the supporting "[[Grotesk Burlesk Tour]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1471565/for-the-record-quick-news-on-marilyn-manson-and-jean-paul-gaultier-bone-crusher-camron-pearl-jam-jimi-hendrix-more/ |title=For The Record: Quick News on Marilyn Manson and Jean Paul Gaultier |author=MTV News Staff |work=[[MTV News]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=April 28, 2003 |access-date=May 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505052930/http://www.mtv.com/news/1471565/for-the-record-quick-news-on-marilyn-manson-and-jean-paul-gaultier-bone-crusher-camron-pearl-jam-jimi-hendrix-more/ |archive-date=May 5, 2016}}</ref> The [[greatest hits album|greatest hits]] compilation ''[[Lest We Forget: The Best Of]]'' was released in 2004.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/66218/manson-to-tour-against-all-gods|title=Manson To Tour 'Against All Gods'|magazine=Billboard|date=October 5, 2004|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803110307/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/66218/manson-to-tour-against-all-gods|archive-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref>
{{Quote box|quote="He's very savvy in that he lets people think things about him or plays into things to see what will happen, almost like a [[performance art]]ist. He's a [[visionary]] in a way, because he identified a culture that was coming and now that culture is everywhere."|source = —[[Billy Corgan]] on Marilyn Manson, 2014<ref>{{cite web |last=Ewens |first= Hannah |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jul/29/marilyn-manson-evolution-justin-bieber |title=The evolution of Marilyn Manson: from Columbine scapegoat to Belieber |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=July 29, 2016 |access-date=February 12, 2022 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201034708/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jul/29/marilyn-manson-evolution-justin-bieber |archive-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref>
