After a three-year hiatus, in which the vocalist pursued other interests,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/20476 |title=Marilyn Manson Unleashes 'Horrorpilation'|author=Bychawski, Adam|work=[[NME]]|date=July 18, 2005|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617131709/http://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/20476 |archive-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> the band returned with 2007's ''[[Eat Me, Drink Me]]''. The album's lyrical content largely related to the dissolution of Manson's marriage to [[Dita Von Teese]] and his affair with 19-year-old actress [[Evan Rachel Wood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2014/07/marilyn-manson-2007-spin-cover-story-return-of-the-living-dead/|title=Marilyn Manson: Return of the Living Dead|author=Ames, Jonathan|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=May 2007|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413024909/http://www.spin.com/2014/07/marilyn-manson-2007-spin-cover-story-return-of-the-living-dead/|archive-date=April 13, 2016}}</ref> Seventh studio album ''[[The High End of Low]]'' was released in 2009, and was their final album issued by Interscope. While promoting the record, Manson made a series of disparaging comments about the label and its artistic censorship, as well as its president [[Jimmy Iovine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-im-not-trying-to-be-reborn-im-trying-to-transform/|title=Marilyn Manson: I'm Not Trying To Be Reborn, I'm Trying to Transform|author=Hartmann, Graham|work=[[Loudwire]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|date=April 17, 2012|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624032043/http://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-im-not-trying-to-be-reborn-im-trying-to-transform/|archive-date=June 24, 2016}}</ref> Manson signed a lucrative recording contract with British independent record label [[Cooking Vinyl]] in 2011, with the band and label sharing profits equally after the label recouped costs associated with marketing, promotion and distribution.<ref name="Indie">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-marilynmanson-idUSTRE6A71DA20101108|title=Marilyn Manson: Antichrist indie star|author=Paine, Andre|magazine=Billboard|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=November 8, 2010|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427221051/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-marilynmanson-idUSTRE6A71DA20101108|archive-date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> The first album released under the deal was 2012's ''[[Born Villain]]''.<ref name="Vain">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/499428/marilyn-manson-johnny-depp-cover-youre-so-vain|title=Marilyn Manson & Johnny Depp Cover 'You're So Vain'|author=Sherman, Maria|magazine=Billboard|date=March 20, 2012|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224230342/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/499428/marilyn-manson-johnny-depp-cover-youre-so-vain|archive-date=December 24, 2016}}</ref> Lead single "[[No Reflection]]" earned the band their fourth Grammy nomination.<ref name="Grammys"/> Subsequent albums were released in the United States by [[Loma Vista Recordings]], beginning with 2015's ''[[The Pale Emperor]]'', which was widely seen as a return to form<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/18/arts/music/a-dark-prince-steps-into-the-light-.html?_r=0|title=A Dark Prince Steps Into the Light|author=Ryzik, Melena|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 15, 2015|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426042014/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/18/arts/music/a-dark-prince-steps-into-the-light-.html?_r=0|archive-date=April 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/01/20/marilyn-manson-the-pale-emperor_n_6507210.html|title=Why Marilyn Manson's 'The Pale Emperor' Is A 'F*ck You' To The Devil|author=Brophy, Aaron|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=January 20, 2015|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306204743/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/01/20/marilyn-manson-the-pale-emperor_n_6507210.html|archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref> and was a commercial success upon release.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6451196/fall-out-boy-marilyn-manson-rock-chart-debuts|title=Who Says Rock Is Dead? Marilyn Manson, Fall Out Boy & More Notch Big Debuts|author=Lynch, Joe|magazine=Billboard|date=January 28, 2015|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130094435/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6451196/fall-out-boy-marilyn-manson-rock-chart-debuts|archive-date=January 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/chris-sosa/marilyn-manson-just-made-_b_6587838.html|title=Marilyn Manson Just Made an Unexpected Comeback|author=Sosa, Chris|work=The Huffington Post|date=February 2, 2015|access-date=February 12, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809094209/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/chris-sosa/marilyn-manson-just-made-_b_6587838.html|archive-date=August 9, 2016}}</ref>

''[[Heaven Upside Down]]'' followed in 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2017/09/marilyn-manson-we-know-where-you-fucking-live-stream-new-album-heaven-upside-down-release-date/ |title=Marilyn Manson Releases Single 'We Know Where You Fucking Live', Announces New Album Heaven Upside Down |author=Gaca, Anna |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=September 11, 2017 |access-date=September 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911210600/https://www.spin.com/2017/09/marilyn-manson-we-know-where-you-fucking-live-stream-new-album-heaven-upside-down-release-date/ |archive-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> with its single "[[Kill4Me]]" becoming the band's highest-peaking single ever on ''Billboard''{{'s}} [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/marilyn-manson/chart-history/rtt/|title=Marilyn Manson – Mainstream Rock Airplay|magazine=Billboard|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref> While [[Heaven Upside Down Tour|touring in support of the record]], Manson was injured by two large falling stage props as he performed on stage at the [[Hammerstein Ballroom]] in New York, breaking his [[fibula]] in two places, requiring a plate and ten screws to be inserted in the bone, as well as another screw in his ankle, which he had sprained during a show in [[Pittsburgh]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-41458046|title=Marilyn Manson crushed by prop on stage|date=October 1, 2017|access-date=October 1, 2017|work=BBC News|archive-date=October 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001063502/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-41458046|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/marilyn-manson-addresses-stage-mishap-delayed-2017-tour-194531499.html|title=Marilyn Manson addresses scary stage accident: 'The pain was excruciating'|date=October 12, 2017|website=Yahoo.com|access-date=October 13, 2017|via=Yahoo|archive-date=October 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013071910/https://www.yahoo.com/music/marilyn-manson-addresses-stage-mishap-delayed-2017-tour-194531499.html|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[God's Gonna Cut You Down#Marilyn Manson version|God's Gonna Cut You Down]]" was released as a non-album single in 2019,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/10/marilyn-manson-gods-gonna-cut-you-down-stream/ |title=Stream Marilyn Manson - 'God's Gonna Cut You Down' |first=Robin|last=Bacior |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=October 18, 2019 |access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/marilyn-manson-releases-new-single-video-gods-gonna-cut-you-down-2558487 |title=Marilyn Manson releases ominous video for new single 'God's Gonna Cut You Down' |first=Karen|last=Gwee|magazine=[[NME]] |date=October 18, 2019 |access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref> and is the band's highest-peaking single on ''Billboard''{{'s}} [[Hot Rock Songs]] and [[Rock Digital Songs]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/marilyn-manson/chart-history/ark/|title=Marilyn Manson – Hot Rock Songs|magazine=Billboard|access-date=March 4, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/marilyn-manson/chart-history/rkt/|title=Marilyn Manson – Rock Digital Songs|magazine=Billboard|access-date=March 4, 2022}}</ref> Their most recent studio album, 2020's ''[[We Are Chaos]]'', was the band's tenth top ten release on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name="ten">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9452588/youngboy-never-broke-again-top-billboard-200-number-one|title=YoungBoy Never Broke Again Achieves Third No. 1 Album in Less Than a Year on the Billboard 200 Chart With 'Top'|author=Caulfield, Keith|magazine=Billboard|date=September 20, 2020|access-date=September 20, 2020|archive-date=September 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924004056/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9452588/youngboy-never-broke-again-top-billboard-200-number-one|url-status=live}}</ref>

According to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], the band sold 8.7 million albums alone in the United States as of 2011.<ref name="Indie"/> Three of their albums received platinum awards from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], and a further three received gold certifications.<ref>{{cite certification|region=United States|artist=Marilyn Manson|access-date=February 12, 2022}}</ref> Ten of their releases debuted in the top ten of the ''Billboard'' 200, including two number-one albums.<ref name="ten"/> In the United Kingdom, the band are certified for sales of almost 1.75 million units.<ref>{{cite certification|region=United Kingdom|artist=Marilyn Manson|access-date=February 12, 2022}}</ref> Marilyn Manson has sold over 50 million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/marilyn-manson-the-vampire-of-the-hollywood-hills-20150106?page=2 |title=Marilyn Manson: The Vampire of the Hollywood Hills |author=Hedegaard, Erik |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 6, 2015 |access-date=August 3, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926062752/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/marilyn-manson-the-vampire-of-the-hollywood-hills-20150106?page=2 |archive-date=September 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jan/18/marilyn-manson-i-created-a-fake-world |title=Marilyn Manson: 'I created a fake world because I didn't like the one I was living in' |first=Carole |last=Cadwalladr |author-link=Carole Cadwalladr |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 18, 2015 |access-date=August 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827015623/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jan/18/marilyn-manson-i-created-a-fake-world |archive-date=August 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/01/21/marilyn-manson-on-charlie-hebdo-and-why-you-should-avoid-foursomes.html |title=Marilyn Manson on Charlie Hebdo and Why You Should Avoid Foursomes |author=Stern, Marlow |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=January 21, 2015 |access-date=August 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705034949/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/01/21/marilyn-manson-on-charlie-hebdo-and-why-you-should-avoid-foursomes.html |archive-date=July 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/marilyn_manson_to_receive_apmas_2016_icon_award |title=Marilyn Manson to receive APMAs 2016 Icon Award - News |author=Al-Sharif, Rabab |work=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=May 13, 2016 |access-date=August 3, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822133206/http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/marilyn_manson_to_receive_apmas_2016_icon_award |archive-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref>

===Musical collaborations===
In addition to his work with the band, Manson has collaborated extensively with other musicians.<ref name="Collaboration">{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-a-z-of-marilyn-manson|title=The A–Z Of Marilyn Manson|author=Lloyd, Gavin|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|date=January 14, 2015|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref> [[Cello rock]] act [[Rasputina (band)|Rasputina]] opened for the band throughout the "[[Dead to the World Tour]]", the controversial tour supporting ''Antichrist Superstar''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1431807/marilyn-manson-may-be-shut-out-of-richmond-virginia/ |title=Marilyn Manson May Be Shut Out Of Richmond, Virginia |author=MTV News Staff |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=April 16, 1997 |access-date=January 11, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111102250/http://www.mtv.com/news/1431807/marilyn-manson-may-be-shut-out-of-richmond-virginia/ |archive-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> Lead vocalist [[Melora Creager]] performed cello and backing vocals for the band, most notably for renditions of "[[Apple of Sodom]]", a live version of which appeared as a [[b-side]] on Manson's 1998 single "The Dope Show".<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=The Dope Show |type=liner notes |others=Marilyn Manson |publisher=Interscope Records |year=1998 |id=INTDS–95599}}</ref> Manson also created three remixes of the song "Transylvanian Concubine", two of which appeared on their 1997 EP ''[[Transylvanian Regurgitations]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=MTV News Staff|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1431792/marilyn-manson-rasputina-remix-to-creep-into-stores/|title=Marilyn Manson-Rasputina Remix To Creep Into Stores|work=MTV|publisher=Viacom Media Networks|date=May 29, 1997|access-date=March 4, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190118084845/http://www.mtv.com/news/1431792/marilyn-manson-rasputina-remix-to-creep-into-stores/|archive-date=January 18, 2019}}</ref> Manson befriended [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] vocalist [[Billy Corgan]] in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1431817/manson-teams-with-corgan-sparks-concert-ratings-talk/|title=Manson Teams With Corgan, Sparks Concert Rating Talk|work=MTV|date=March 6, 1997|access-date=March 4, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110093731/http://www.mtv.com/news/1431817/manson-teams-with-corgan-sparks-concert-ratings-talk/|archive-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> and performed renditions of "[[Eye (song)|Eye]]" and "The Beautiful People" alongside that band at the 1997 edition of [[Bridge School Benefit]] concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/the-smashing-pumpkins/watch-the-smashing-pumpkins-rock-san-francisco-on/|title=Watch The Smashing Pumpkins Rock San Francisco on This Day in 1997|author=Manno, Lizzie|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=October 18, 2018|access-date=December 30, 2021}}</ref> Manson frequently consulted Corgan during the early stages of recording ''Mechanical Animals''. Referring to its inclusion of glam rock influences, Corgan advised Manson that "This is definitely the right direction" but to "go all the way with it. Don't just hint at it".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-mansons-new-happy-face-19980902 |title=Marilyn Manson's New (Happy) Face |author=Ali, Lorraine |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=September 2, 1998 |access-date=April 19, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415215503/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-mansons-new-happy-face-19980902 |archive-date=April 15, 2016|author-link=Lorraine Ali}}</ref> In 2015, Marilyn Manson and the Smashing Pumpkins embarked on a [[double feature|co-healining]] tour titled "[[The End Times Tour]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/lasvegas/lasvegasnow/la-tr-lvn-las-vegas-shows-smashing-pumpkins-marilyn-manson-20150405-story.html |title=It's the end times for The Smashing Pumpkins and Marilyn Manson in Las Vegas|author=Stapleton, Susan|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 6, 2015|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref>

To promote ''Mechanical Animals'' in 1998, the band embarked on their first co-headlining concert tour: the "[[Beautiful Monsters Tour]]" with [[Hole (band)|Hole]].<ref name="Schedule">{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/511731/marilyn-manson-hole-schedule-beautiful-monsters-tour/ |title=Marilyn Manson, Hole Schedule 'Beautiful Monsters' Tour |author=Kaufman, Gil |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=January 27, 1999 |access-date=April 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727091742/http://www.mtv.com/news/511731/marilyn-manson-hole-schedule-beautiful-monsters-tour/ |archive-date=July 27, 2015}}</ref> The tour was problematic,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/512787/best-of-99-boston-promoter-says-hole-dropping-off-manson-tour/ |title=Best Of '99: Boston Promoter Says Hole Dropping Off Manson Tour |author=Kaufman, Gil |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=March 10, 1999 |access-date=April 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317083515/http://www.mtv.com/news/512787/best-of-99-boston-promoter-says-hole-dropping-off-manson-tour/ |archive-date=March 17, 2016}}</ref> with Manson and Hole vocalist [[Courtney Love]] frequently insulting one another both on-stage and during interviews.<ref name="Walks">{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1430056/hole-walks-out-on-tour-manson-injury-postpones-several-dates/ |title=Hole Walks Out On Tour, Manson Injury Postpones Several Dates |author=MTV News Staff |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=March 15, 1999 |access-date=April 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220031236/http://www.mtv.com/news/1430056/hole-walks-out-on-tour-manson-injury-postpones-several-dates |archive-date=December 20, 2014}}</ref> Private disputes also arose over finances, as Hole were unwittingly financing most of Manson's production costs, which were disproportionately high relative to Hole's.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/512758/hole-threaten-to-drop-off-marilyn-manson-joint-tour/ |title=Hole Threaten To Drop Off Marilyn Manson Joint Tour |author=Kaufman, Gil |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=March 11, 1999 |access-date=April 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728032221/http://www.mtv.com/news/512758/hole-threaten-to-drop-off-marilyn-manson-joint-tour/ |archive-date=July 28, 2015}}</ref> The tour was to consist of thirty-seven dates,<ref name="Schedule"/> although Hole left after nine.<ref name="Walks"/> When Hole departed from the tour, it was renamed the "[[Rock Is Dead Tour]]", with [[Jack Off Jill]] announced as one of the support acts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1430051/manson-resumes-tour-without-hole-taps-nashville-pussy-and-jack-off-jill-for-upcoming-dates/ |title=Manson Resumes Tour Without Hole, Taps Nashville Pussy And Jack Off Jill For Upcoming Dates |author=MTV News Staff |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=March 22, 1999 |access-date=April 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515192019/http://www.mtv.com/news/1430051/manson-resumes-tour-without-hole-taps-nashville-pussy-and-jack-off-jill-for-upcoming-dates/ |archive-date=May 15, 2016}}</ref> Manson had produced many of Jack Off Jill's demo recordings in the early 90s, and later wrote the [[liner notes]] to their 2006 compilation ''[[Humid Teenage Mediocrity 1992–1996]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/humid-teenage-mediocrity-1992-1995-mw0000568065|title=Human Teenage Mediocrity: 1992-1995 – Jack Off Jill|author=Collar, Camilla|work=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=March 4, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Humid Teenage Mediocrity 1992–1996|type=liner notes|chapter=Booklet|others=Marilyn Manson|publisher=[[Sympathy for the Record Industry]]|year=2020|id=SFTRI- 772|location=Los Angeles, United States}}</ref>

Manson launched his own vanity label in 2000, [[Posthuman Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/3082|title=Manson Launches New Posthuman Label|work=[[NME]]|date=April 12, 2000|access-date=March 4, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021101210/https://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/3082|archive-date=October 21, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The label released two albums – the 2000 soundtrack to ''[[Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2 (soundtrack)|Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2]]'' and [[Godhead (band)|Godhead]]'s 2001 album ''[[2000 Years of Human Error]]'' – before being dissolved in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/marilyn-mansons-50-greatest-achievements|title=Marilyn Manson's 50 Greatest Achievements|work=[[Kerrang!]]|date=January 5, 2019|access-date=March 4, 2022}}</ref> The latter album sold over 100,000 copies in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/godhead-signs-with-driven-music-group/|title=Godhead Signs With Driven Music Group|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=June 6, 2008|access-date=February 7, 2022}}</ref> and featured him performing vocals on the track "Break You Down".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xyoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA67|title=CMJ New Music Monthly {{!}} Reviews {{!}} Godhead|author=Richardson, Sean|work=[[CMJ New Music]]|date=February 2001|page=67|access-date=March 4, 2022}}</ref> He performed vocals on "Redeemer", a song written by [[Korn]] vocalist [[Jonathan Davis]] that featured on the 2002 album ''[[Queen of the Damned: Music from the Motion Picture]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/queen-of-the-damned-orginal-motion-picture-soundtrack--mw0000218820|title=Queen of the Damned &#91;Original Motion Picture Soundtrack&#93;|author=Ruhlmann, William|work=AllMusic|access-date=March 14, 2022}}</ref> Davis had been prevented from singing the song due to contractual issues with his record label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1451248/korns-davis-uses-stunt-double-for-vampire-movie-soundtrack/|title=Korn's Davis Uses Stunt Double For Vampire Movie Soundtrack|author=Moss, Corey|work=MTV News|date=November 29, 2001|access-date=March 14, 2022}}</ref> Manson also contributed a remix of the [[Linkin Park]] song "By Myself" to that band's remix album ''[[Reanimation (Linkin Park album)|Reanimation]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/linkin-parks-hybrid-theory-certified-12-times-platinum-in-u-s/|title=Linkin Park's 'Hybrid Theory' Certified 12 Times Platinum In U.S.|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=September 22, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2022}}</ref> and collaborated with [[Marco Beltrami]] to create the score for the 2002 film ''[[Resident Evil (film)|Resident Evil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/music/spotlight/haslinger-manson-help-resident-evil-score-hits-all-right-notes-1201943565/|title=The Music of 'Resident Evil': From Moody to Heavy Metal|author=Barker, Andrew|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 16, 2016|access-date=March 9, 2022}}</ref>

He performed vocals on the [[Chew Fu]] GhettoHouse Fix remix of [[Lady Gaga]]'s "[[LoveGame]]", which was featured as a b-side on the song's single in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-not-a-big-fan-of-lady-gaga/|title=Marilyn Manson Not a Big Fan of Lady Gaga|first=Chad|last=Childers|website=Loudwire}}</ref> He was a featured vocalist on "Can't Haunt Me",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://popcrush.com/skylar-grey-recalls-approaching-marilyn-manson-for-cant-haunt-me/|title=Skylar Grey Recalls Approaching Marilyn Manson for 'Can't Haunt Me'|first=Amy|last=Sciarretto|website=PopCrush}}</ref> a track recorded in 2011 for [[Skylar Grey]]'s unreleased album ''Invinsible''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/eminem-155-1268142|title=Skylar Grey: 'Eminem is scared to leave the house'|website=[[NME]]|date=August 23, 2011}}</ref> He appeared on "[[Bad Girl (Avril Lavigne song)|Bad Girl]]", a song from [[Avril Lavigne]]'s 2013 [[Avril Lavigne (album)|self-titled album]],<ref name="Collaboration"/> and featured on the song "Hypothetical" from [[Emigrate (band)|Emigrate]]'s 2014 album ''[[Silent So Long]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/emigrate-collaborations-lemmy-marilyn-manson/|title=Emigrate Discuss Collaborations With Lemmy + Marilyn Manson|first=Spencer|last=Kaufman|website=Loudwire}}</ref> [[New Orleans]] brass ensemble [[the Soul Rebels]] performed "The Beautiful People" alongside Manson at the 2015 edition of the Japanese [[Summer Sonic Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nola.com/entertainment_life/music/article_210b8224-4ccb-54b4-8cff-7e49c4889a0e.html|title=In Japan, the Soul Rebels perform with Marilyn Manson, Macklemore & Ryan Lewis: Watch|first=Alison|last=Fensterstock|website=[[Nola.com]]}}</ref> Manson recorded vocals on a cover of Bowie's "[[Cat People (Putting Out Fire)]]" for country musician [[Shooter Jennings]]'s 2016 album ''[[Countach (For Giorgio)]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/shooter-jennings-enlists-marilyn-manson-brandi-carlile-for-countach-20160104 |title=Shooter Jennings Enlists Marilyn Manson, Brandi Carlile for 'Countach' |first=Andrew |last=Leahey |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=January 4, 2016 |access-date=March 10, 2022 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505073525/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/shooter-jennings-enlists-marilyn-manson-brandi-carlile-for-countach-20160104 |archive-date=May 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/02/marilyn-manson-covers-the-hell-out-of-david-bowies-cat-people-listen/ |title=Marilyn Manson covers the hell out of David Bowie's 'Cat People' — listen |first=Ben |last=Kaye |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=February 18, 2016 |access-date=March 10, 2022 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628133202/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/02/marilyn-manson-covers-the-hell-out-of-david-bowies-cat-people-listen/ |archive-date=June 28, 2016}}</ref> The two were introduced in 2013 by Manson's then-bassist [[Twiggy Ramirez]],<ref name="Guitar">{{cite web |url=https://www.guitarworld.com/features/shooter-jennings-marilyn-mansons-miraculous-poetic-ability-doesnt-grow-cold-like-a-lot-of-peoples-songwriting |title=Shooter Jennings: 'Marilyn Manson's miraculous poetic ability doesn't grow cold, like a lot of people's songwriting' |author=Horsley, Jonathan |work=[[Guitar World]] |date=September 23, 2020 |access-date=March 10, 2022 |archive-date=October 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201027063706/https://www.guitarworld.com/features/shooter-jennings-marilyn-mansons-miraculous-poetic-ability-doesnt-grow-cold-like-a-lot-of-peoples-songwriting |url-status=live}}</ref> and the pair first collaborated that same year on a song for the soundtrack to television series ''[[Sons of Anarchy]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.revolvermag.com/music/marilyn-manson-chaos-collaboration-how-elton-john-made-him-cry |title=Marilyn Manson on 'CHAOS,' Collaboration, How Elton John Made Him Cry |first=Sara |last=Taylor |author-link=Youth Code |work=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]] |date=September 1, 2020 |access-date=September 9, 2020 |archive-date=September 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200910201252/https://www.revolvermag.com/music/marilyn-manson-chaos-collaboration-how-elton-john-made-him-cry |url-status=live}}</ref> Their version of the song, "Join the Human Gang", remains unreleased, but the track was eventually rewritten and released by [[The White Buffalo (musician)|The White Buffalo]] as "Come Join the Murder".<ref name="Guitar"/> Jennings later produced Manson's 2020 album ''We Are Chaos''.<ref name="Guitar"/>

Manson has collaborated with numerous [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] artists. In 1998, he featured on "The Omen (Damien II)", a track on [[DMX]]'s album ''[[Flesh of My Flesh, Blood of My Blood]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/10-rock-collaborations-you-wont-believe-happened|title=10 Rock Collaborations You Won't Believe Happened|website=Kerrang!}}</ref><ref name="NYT">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/09/arts/music/dmx-dead-songs-playlist.html|title=DMX: Hear 10 Essential Songs|first=Christopher R.|last=Weingarten|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 9, 2021}}</ref> Following the Columbine High School massacre, Manson was mentioned in the lyrics to [[Eminem]]'s "[[The Way I Am (Eminem song)|The Way I Am]]" from ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP]]'', in the lyric "When a dude's getting bullied and he shoots up the school and they blame it on Marilyn". Manson appeared in the song's music video, and a remix created by [[Danny Lohner]] and featuring Manson appeared on special editions of ''The Marshall Mathers LP''. Manson also joined Eminem on-stage for several live performances of the track, one of which featured on Eminem's 2002 video album ''[[All Access Europe]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.revolvermag.com/music/watch-marilyn-manson-join-eminem-unhinged-way-i-am-performance-2001|title=Watch Marilyn Manson Join Eminem for Unhinged "The Way I Am" Performance in 2001|date=August 31, 2018|website=Revolver}}</ref> He featured on "Pussy Wet", a song on [[Gucci Mane]]'s 2013 [[mixtape]] ''Diary of a Trap God'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2013/09/13/hear-gucci-mane-and-marilyn-mansons-collaboration-pussy-wet|title=Hear Gucci Mane and Marilyn Manson's Collaboration, "Pussy Wet"|website=The FADER}}</ref> and provided vocals on the song "Marilyn Manson" on the 2020 mixtape ''Floor Seats II'' by [[ASAP Ferg]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/best-new-music-asap-ferg-polo-g-lil-wayne|title=Best New Music This Week: ASAP Ferg, Polo G, Lil Wayne, and More|website=Complex}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/asap-ferg-floor-seats-ii-album-announcement-dennis-rodman-9451283/|title=A$AP Ferg Sits Down With Dennis Rodman to Announce 'Floor Seats II' Album|first=Heran|last=Mamo|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=September 17, 2020}}</ref>

Alongside [[DaBaby]], Manson co-wrote and was a featured artist on "[[Jail pt 2]]", a song on [[Kanye West]]'s 2021 album ''[[Donda]]''.<ref name="West">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/kanye-west-defends-performing-with-marilyn-manson-and-dababy-3088322|title=Kanye West defends performing with Marilyn Manson and DaBaby|website=[[NME]]|date=November 5, 2021}}</ref> Manson and DaBaby appeared alongside West at several events promoting the album, including at a listening event held at [[Soldier Field]] in August, and at one of West's Sunday Church Services in October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-08-27/kanye-west-marilyn-manson-dababy-donda|title=From MAGA to Manson: Kanye West brings out alleged sexual abuser Marilyn Manson at 'Donda' event|date=August 27, 2021|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/kanye-west-joined-by-marilyn-manson-justin-bieber-sunday-service-3083905|title=Kanye West sparks controversy as Marilyn Manson appears on Sunday Service|website=[[NME]]|date=October 31, 2021}}</ref> The appearances attracted significant media attention and controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/kanye-west-sparks-controversy-after-inviting-dababy-marilyn-manson-stage-n1277798|title=Kanye West's 'Donda' listening party features DaBaby, Marilyn Manson|website=NBC News}}</ref> West said the trio collaborated on a total of five songs.<ref name="West"/> The album was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album]], which entitled Manson to a co-nomination credit for his work on the song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/marilyn-manson-grammy-nomination-kanye-b1963086.html|title=Marilyn Manson has been nominated for Grammy|date=November 23, 2021|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/music-news/marilyn-manson-loses-2022-grammy-nomination-1235056319/|title=Marilyn Manson Loses Grammy Nomination for Best Rap Song|first=Abbey|last=White|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 2, 2021}}</ref> Manson continued his collaboration with West for the follow-up album, ''[[Donda 2]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequence.net/2022/02/marilyn-manson-confirms-kanye-west-donda-2/|title=Marilyn Manson confirms he's contributing to Kanye West's upcoming album Donda 2|date=February 2, 2022}}</ref> West collaborator [[Digital Nas]] said Manson was in the recording studio "every day" while the album was recorded, and explained that West "doesn't want Marilyn to play rap beats. He wants Marilyn to play what he makes, and then Ye will take parts of that and sample parts of that and use parts of that, like he did [generally when making] ''[[Yeezus]]''."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/marilyn-manson-confirms-work-kanye-west-donda-1675326|title=Marilyn Manson confirms he is continuing to work with Kanye West|first=Emma|last=Nolan|date=February 2, 2022|website=Newsweek}}</ref> Manson band-member [[Tim Skold]] has confirmed he was involved in the process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/marilyn-manson-confirms-hes-working-on-kanye-wests-donda-2-3152637|title=Marilyn Manson confirms he's working on Kanye West's 'Donda 2'|website=[[NME]]|date=February 3, 2022}}</ref>

While with The Spooky Kids, Manson teamed with [[Jeordie White]] (also known as Twiggy Ramirez) and Stephen Gregory Bier Jr. (also known as [[Madonna Wayne Gacy]]) in two side-projects: Satan on Fire, a faux-[[Christian metal]] ensemble where he played bass guitar, and drums in Mrs. Scabtree, a collaborative band formed with White and then girlfriend [[Jessicka]] (vocalist with the band [[Jack Off Jill]]) as a way to combat contractual agreements that prohibited Marilyn Manson from playing in certain clubs.{{Citation needed|date=February 2022}}

=== Film and television ===
[[File:Marilyn Manson Cannes.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Manson at the [[2006 Cannes Film Festival]]]]

Manson made his film debut in 1997, as an actor in [[David Lynch]]'s ''[[Lost Highway (1997 film)|Lost Highway]]''. Since then he has appeared in many minor roles and cameos, including ''[[Party Monster (2003 film)|Party Monster]]''; then-girlfriend [[Rose McGowan]]'s 1999 film ''[[Jawbreaker (film)|Jawbreaker]]''; [[Asia Argento]]'s 2004 film ''[[The Heart Is Deceitful Above All Things]]''; ''[[Rise: Blood Hunter|Rise]]''; ''[[The Hire]]: Beat The Devil'', the sixth installment in the [[BMW films]] series; and [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s comedy-drama TV series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]'' in 2013, in which Manson portrayed himself. He also appeared on HBO's ''[[Eastbound & Down]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maeby |first1=Liana |title=How weird was Marilyn Mansons cameo on Eastbound and Down? |url=http://www.hitfix.com/comedy/how-weird-was-marilyn-mansons-cameo-on-eastbound-and-down |website=Hitfix |access-date=April 17, 2015 |date=November 4, 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417173801/http://www.hitfix.com/comedy/how-weird-was-marilyn-mansons-cameo-on-eastbound-and-down |archive-date=April 17, 2015 }}</ref> of which Manson is reportedly a longtime fan,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vena |first1=Jocelyn |title=Marilyn Manson 'Obsessed' With 'Eastbound And Down,' Director Says |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1647329/marilyn-manson-obsessed-with-eastbound-and-down-director-says/ |website=MTV News |access-date=April 17, 2015 |date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501085546/http://www.mtv.com/news/1647329/marilyn-manson-obsessed-with-eastbound-and-down-director-says/ |archive-date=May 1, 2015 }}</ref> and had lobbied to appear on for years; and ABC's ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]'', for which he provided the voice of the character "Shadow".<ref>{{cite news|last=Neumyer|first=Scott|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-joining-once-upon-a-time-cast-100225/|title=Marilyn Manson Joining 'Once Upon a Time' Cast|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 18, 2013|access-date=October 14, 2021}}</ref>

He was interviewed in [[Michael Moore]]'s political documentary ''[[Bowling for Columbine]]'' (2002) discussing possible motivations for the [[Columbine High School massacre|Columbine massacre]] and allegations that his music was somehow a factor.{{citation needed|date=October 2021}} He has appeared in animated form in ''[[Clone High]]'' and participated in several episodes of the MTV series ''[[Celebrity Deathmatch]]'', becoming the show's unofficial champion and mascot; he often performed the voice for his [[claymation|claymated]] puppet, and contributed the song "[[Astonishing Panorama of the Endtimes]]" to the soundtrack album.{{citation needed|date=October 2021}} In July 2005, Manson told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' that he was shifting his focus from music to filmmaking – "I just don't think the world is worth putting music into right now. I no longer want to make art that other people – particularly record companies – are turning into a product. I just want to make art."{{citation needed|date=October 2021}} [[Johnny Depp]] reportedly used Manson as his inspiration for his performance as [[Willy Wonka]] in the film ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/arid-30183322.html|title=Depp inspired by Manson Manson|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=January 5, 2005|access-date=October 14, 2021}}</ref> Manson himself expressed interest in playing the role of Willy Wonka in the film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman |first1=Bill |title=HELL ROCKER MANSON: I'LL PLAY WONKA AS 'SATAN' |url=https://nypost.com/2001/01/31/hell-rocker-manson-ill-play-wonka-as-satan/ |website=New York Post |publisher=New York Post |date=January 31, 2001 |access-date=April 17, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422221801/http://nypost.com/2001/01/31/hell-rocker-manson-ill-play-wonka-as-satan/ |archive-date=April 22, 2015 }}</ref>

[[File:Manson en concierto 6.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Manson performing in São Paulo in 2007 during the [[Rape of the World Tour]]]]
He had been working on his directorial debut, ''Phantasmagoria: The Visions of Lewis Carroll'', a project that has been in [[development hell]] since 2004, with Manson also set to portray the role of [[Lewis Carroll]], author of ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''. Initially announced as a web-only release, it was later decided to give the estimated $4.2&nbsp;million budget film a conventional cinema release, with a slated release date of mid-2007. The film was to have an original music soundtrack with previously unreleased songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=15724_0_2_0_C/ |title=Marilyn Manson announces details first low budget film |work=SIDE-LINE.com |date=July 5, 2006 |access-date=February 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622150430/http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=15724_0_2_0_C%2F |archive-date=June 22, 2008 }}</ref> Production of the film had been postponed indefinitely until after the ''Eat Me, Drink Me'' tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=76734 |title='Phantasmagoria' Film Still in Pipeline |work=BLABBERMOUTH.NET |date=July 13, 2007 |access-date=February 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302131148/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=76734 |archive-date=March 2, 2008 }}</ref> In 2010, studio bosses shut down production on the project, reportedly due to viewers' responses to the violent content of clips released on the internet. The film was later officially put on "indefinite production hold".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/coles-violent-film-put-on-indefinite-hold_1165177 |title=Lily Cole &#124; Cole's Violent Film Put on Indefinite Hold |magazine=Contactmusic |date= September 12, 2010|access-date=April 15, 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221041003/http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/coles-violent-film-put-on-indefinite-hold_1165177 |archive-date=February 21, 2011 }}</ref>

However, according to a 2010 interview with co-writer Anthony Silva about the hold, the film was still on and the talk of it being shut down was just a myth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marilynmansonfrance.free.fr/index.php/anthony-silva-exclusive-interview |archive-url=https://archive.today/2012.07.14-145049/http://marilynmansonfrance.free.fr/index.php/anthony-silva-exclusive-interview |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 14, 2012 |title=''Phantasmagoria: The Visions of Anthony Silva'' Exclusive Interview |publisher=Marilynmansonfrance.free.fr |access-date=September 6, 2012}}</ref>
In a June 2013 interview, Manson stated that he had "resurrected" the project, and that [[Roger Avary]] would direct it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mansonwiki.com/wiki/Video_Interview:2013/06/03_Larry_King_Now_Marilyn_Manson_Interview |title=Video Interview:2013/06/03 Larry King Now Marilyn Manson Interview |publisher=Mansonwiki.com |access-date=January 14, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709211658/http://www.mansonwiki.com/wiki/Video_Interview%3A2013/06/03_Larry_King_Now_Marilyn_Manson_Interview |archive-date=July 9, 2015 }}</ref> In a separate interview during the previous year, he said a small crew similar to what he used for his "[[Slo-Mo-Tion]]" music video would be used, and would rather film the movie on an iPhone than not film it at all. In a [[Reddit]] AMA with [[Billy Corgan]] on April 4, 2015, Manson commented that he had withdrawn from the project because the writing process for the film was "so... damaging to my psyche, I've decided I don't want to have anything to do with it", and further commented that the only footage that had been created thus far had been content created for the trailer, which was made in order to promote the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/IAmA/comments/31d131/we_are_billy_corgan_and_marilyn_manson_ask_us/cq0g8hg/?context=1 |title=R/IAmA – We are Billy Corgan and Marilyn Manson. Ask us anything |date=April 3, 2015 |access-date=September 17, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418075246/http://www.reddit.com/r/IAmA/comments/31d131/we_are_billy_corgan_and_marilyn_manson_ask_us |archive-date=April 18, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/brief/60016560/marilyn-manson-damaged-by-axed-film-project?page=all|title=General Archives - Hollywood.com|website=Hollywood.com|access-date=October 1, 2017}}</ref>

Manson appeared in the final season of the TV series ''[[Sons of Anarchy]]'', portraying white supremacist Ron Tully.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/05/29/sons-of-anarchy-marilyn-manson/ |title='Sons of Anarchy' casts Marilyn Manson in recurring role |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=January 14, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118091112/http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/05/29/sons-of-anarchy-marilyn-manson/ |archive-date=January 18, 2015 }}</ref> In January 2016, it was announced that Manson would be joining the cast for season 3 of WGN's ''[[Salem (TV series)|Salem]]''. He played Thomas Dinley, a barber and surgeon described as "the go-to man in Salem, from a shave and a haircut to being leeched, bled, sliced open or sewn up".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-manson-to-guest-star-as-barber-surgeon-on-salem-20160121 |title=Marilyn Manson to Guest Star as Barber/Surgeon on 'Salem' |first=Daniel |last=Kreps |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=January 21, 2016 |access-date=February 9, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131110053/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-manson-to-guest-star-as-barber-surgeon-on-salem-20160121 |archive-date=January 31, 2016 }}</ref> In 2020, Manson was a guest star on the HBO television series ''[[The New Pope]]'', in which he has a personal audience with the series' [[Pope]] and recommends that he visit the prior Pope that lies unconscious in a coma.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.revolvermag.com/culture/see-marilyn-mansons-funny-cameo-john-malkovich-new-pope |title=SEE MARILYN MANSON'S FUNNY CAMEO WITH JOHN MALKOVICH ON 'THE NEW POPE' |date=January 29, 2020 |work=Revolver Magazine |access-date=February 4, 2020 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204071059/https://www.revolvermag.com/culture/see-marilyn-mansons-funny-cameo-john-malkovich-new-pope |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Art ===
[[File:Marilyn Manson - Omega.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Manson as ''Mechanical Animals''{{'}} antagonist/character "Omega"]]
Manson stated in a 2004 interview with ''[[i-D magazine]]'' to have begun his career as a [[watercolor]] painter in 1999 when he made five-minute concept pieces and sold them to drug dealers. On September 13–14, 2002, his first show, The Golden Age of Grotesque, was held at the Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions Centre. ''[[Art in America]]''{{'}}s Max Henry likened them to the works of a "psychiatric patient given materials to use as [[art therapy|therapy]]" and said his work would never be taken seriously in a fine art context, writing that the value was "in their celebrity, not the work".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/620624/20000122/story.jhtml |title=Shocker! Marilyn Manson Can Paint, Art Critics Say |author=Smith, Dakota |work=VH1 News |date=January 24, 2000 |access-date=February 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071204203103/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/620624/20000122/story.jhtml |archive-date=December 4, 2007 }}</ref> On September 14–15, 2004, Manson held a second exhibition on the first night in Paris and the second in [[Berlin]]. The show was named 'Trismegistus' which was also the title of the center piece of the exhibit – a large, three-headed Christ painted onto an antique wood panel from a portable embalmers table.

Manson named his self-proclaimed [[art movement]] Celebritarian Corporation. He has coined a [[slogan]] for the movement: "We will sell our shadow to those who stand within it." In 2005 he said that the Celebritarian Corporation has been "incubating for seven years" which if correct would indicate that Celebritarian Corporation, in some form, started in 1998.<ref name="MTV News">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1512539/20051028/marilyn_manson.jhtml?headlines=true |title=Marilyn Manson Likens His New Guitar God to a Naked Woman |access-date=September 27, 2007 |publisher=MTV News |date=October 28, 2005 |author=Harris, Chris |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116185033/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1512539/20051028/marilyn_manson.jhtml?headlines=true |archive-date=November 16, 2007 }}</ref> Celebritarian Corporation is also the namesake of an [[art gallery]] owned by Manson, called the ''Celebritarian Corporation Gallery of Fine Art'' in Los Angeles for which his third exhibition was the inaugural show. From April 2–17, 2007, his works were on show at the Space 39 Modern & Contemporary art gallery in Fort Myers, Florida. Forty pieces from this show traveled to Germany's Gallery Brigitte Schenk in [[Cologne]] to be publicly exhibited from June 28 – July 28, 2007. Manson revealed a series of 20 paintings in 2010 entitled ''Genealogies of Pain'', an exhibition showcased at Vienna's Kunsthalle gallery which the artist collaborated on with [[David Lynch]].<ref name="The Age">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/art-and-design/marilyn-mansons-art-scarier-than-music-20100630-zjyy.html |location=Melbourne |work=The Age |title=Marilyn Manson's art 'scarier than music' |date=June 30, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701232744/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/art-and-design/marilyn-mansons-art-scarier-than-music-20100630-zjyy.html |archive-date=July 1, 2010 }}</ref>

