Manson has mentioned on at least two occasions that he trademarked the name Marilyn Manson. In an interview at the 2015 [[Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity|Cannes Lions Festival]], he said: "I trademarked the name 'Marilyn Manson' the same way as Walt Disney and Mickey Mouse. It's not a stage name. It's not my legal name. ... Marilyn Manson is owned by Brian Warner, my real name."<ref name="blabber">{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-media-storm-after-columbine-really-shut-down-my-career-entirely/ |title=Marilyn Manson: Media Storm After Columbine 'Really Shut Down My Career Entirely' |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=June 24, 2015 |access-date=July 6, 2016 |archive-date=June 27, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627061551/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-media-storm-after-columbine-really-shut-down-my-career-entirely/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He also mentioned this in a 2013 interview with [[Larry King]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Marilyn Manson |url=http://www.hulu.com/watch/496519 |access-date=July 6, 2016 |series=Larry King Now |series-link=Larry King Now |network=[[Hulu]] |date=June 3, 2013 |number=171 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819135607/http://www.hulu.com/watch/496519 |archive-date=August 19, 2016 }}</ref>  The records of the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] show that he registered four trademarks of the name between 1994 and 1999, protecting entertainment services, merchandising and branding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn74458976&docId=ORC20060103194628#docIndex=13&page=1 |title=USPTO TSDR Case Viewer: Case #74458976 |publisher=[[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] |date=December 20, 1994 |access-date=July 6, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007121720/http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn74458976&docId=ORC20060103194628 |archive-date=October 7, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn75248374&docId=ORC20060126053420#docIndex=11&page=1 |title=USPTO TSDR Case Viewer: Case #75248374 |publisher=[[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] |date=February 24, 1998 |access-date=July 6, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007121500/http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn75248374&docId=ORC20060126053420 |archive-date=October 7, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn74458977&docId=ORC20050331065723#docIndex=20&page=1 |title=USPTO TSDR Case Viewer: Case #74458977 |publisher=[[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] |date=January 10, 1999 |access-date=July 6, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007121508/http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn74458977&docId=ORC20050331065723 |archive-date=October 7, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn75358440&docId=ORC20060206221807#docIndex=12&page=1 |title=USPTO TSDR Case Viewer: Case #75358440 |publisher=[[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] |date=May 11, 1999 |access-date=July 6, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007121551/http://tsdr.uspto.gov/documentviewer?caseId=sn75358440&docId=ORC20060206221807 |archive-date=October 7, 2016 }}</ref>

Manson says he used those trademark registrations to issue [[cease and desist]] orders to media outlets who wrongly blamed him for the [[Columbine High School massacre]]. One journalist had erroneously reported the shooters were "wearing Marilyn Manson makeup and t-shirts", although the reports were soon proved incorrect.<ref name="blabber"/> However, Manson said, "Once the wheels started spinning, [[Fox News]] started going."<ref name="blabber"/> As a result of these accusations, Manson's career was seriously harmed: He was shunned by many venue owners and received numerous death threats.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Reilly |first1=Terry |title=The Crazy World of Trademarks |url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/undertheinfluence/the-crazy-world-of-trademarks-1.3918789 |access-date=January 7, 2017 |agency=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |publisher=CBC Radio |date=January 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106203421/http://www.cbc.ca/radio/undertheinfluence/the-crazy-world-of-trademarks-1.3918789 |archive-date=January 6, 2017 }}</ref>

Manson generally uses the name in lieu of his birth name. Though his mother referred to him by his birth name of Brian, his father opted to refer to his son as simply "Manson" since about 1993, saying, "It's called respect of the artist."<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123 |title=Marilyn Manson: Sympathy for the Devil |first=Neil|last=Strauss|author-link=Neil Strauss |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=January 23, 1997 |access-date=June 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423144646/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123 |archive-date=April 23, 2017 }}</ref>

== Lawsuits ==
In September 1996, former bassist [[Gidget Gein]] negotiated a settlement with Manson where he would receive {{US$|17,500|link=no}} and 20 percent of any royalties paid for recordings and for any songs he had a hand in writing and his share of any other royalties or fees the group earned while he was a member and he could market himself as a former member of Marilyn Manson. This settlement was not honored, however.<ref>[http://www.spookykids.net/articles/Daisy_Suit.htm ''Pushing Up Daisy Berkowitz''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928052813/http://www.spookykids.net/articles/Daisy_Suit.htm |date=September 28, 2011 }}. ''City Link''. Jane Musgrave. 1999.</ref>

Former guitarist and founding member [[Scott Putesky]] (a.k.a. Daisy Berkowitz) filed a $15&nbsp;million lawsuit in a Fort Lauderdale court against the singer, the [[Marilyn Manson (band)|band]] and the band's attorney (David Codikow) in January 1998 after his departure from the group in the spring of 1996. Berkowitz claimed "thousands of dollars in royalties, publishing rights, and performance fees" and filed an attorney malpractice suit against Codikow, alleging that "Codikow represented Warner's interests more than the band's and ... gave Warner disproportionate control.."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431766/daisy-berkowitz-takes-marilyn-manson-court.jhtml |title=Daisy Berkowitz Takes Marilyn Manson To Court |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=January 26, 1998 |access-date=March 21, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623183528/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431766/daisy-berkowitz-takes-marilyn-manson-court.jhtml |archive-date=June 23, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Bendersky |first=Ari |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-manson-sued-by-former-member-19970924 |title=Marilyn Manson Sued By Former Member |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=September 24, 1997 |access-date=June 8, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130802034631/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/marilyn-manson-sued-by-former-member-19970924 |archive-date=August 2, 2013 }}</ref> By October of that year, the suit had been settled out of court for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431734/manson-settles-daisy-berkowitz-lawsuit-denies-label-pressured-him-do-so.jhtml |title=Manson Settles Daisy Berkowitz Lawsuit, Denies Label Pressured Him To Do So |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=October 14, 1998 |access-date=March 21, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623183511/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431734/manson-settles-daisy-berkowitz-lawsuit-denies-label-pressured-him-do-so.jhtml |archive-date=June 23, 2012 }}</ref>

On November 30, 1998, a few days after the band accumulated "[a] total [of] more than $25,000" in backstage and hotel room damages during the [[Poughkeepsie, New York]], stop of their [[Mechanical Animals Tour]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431728/marilyn-manson-wrecks-backstage-area-hotel-rooms-rock-roll-melee.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson Wrecks Backstage Area, Hotel Rooms in Rock & Roll Melee |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=November 25, 1998 |access-date=March 21, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623183545/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431728/marilyn-manson-wrecks-backstage-area-hotel-rooms-rock-roll-melee.jhtml |archive-date=June 23, 2012 }}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|SPIN]]'' editor Craig Marks filed a $24-million lawsuit against Manson and his [[bodyguard]]s. On February 19, 1999, Manson counter-sued Marks for libel, slander and defamation, seeking {{US$|40{{nbsp}}million}} in reparation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/512301/19990220/index.jhtml |title=Manson Countersues Ex-Spin Editor For $40M |publisher=[[VH1]] |date=February 20, 1999 |access-date=April 6, 2011}}{{dead link|date=March 2016}}</ref> Marks later dropped the lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2009/07/29/marilyn-manson-threatens-journalists-criticize.html |title=Marilyn Manson Threatens Journalists Who Criticize Him |work=[[Fox News]] |date=July 29, 2009 |access-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030080919/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2009/07/29/marilyn-manson-threatens-journalists-criticize.html |archive-date=October 30, 2016 }}</ref> Manson apologized for the Poughkeepsie incident and offered to make financial restitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431727/did-manson-spin-out-control.jhtml |title=Did Manson "Spin" Out of Control? |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=November 30, 1998 |access-date=March 21, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623183450/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431727/did-manson-spin-out-control.jhtml |archive-date=June 23, 2012 }}</ref><ref name="AP#129">{{cite journal |first=John |last=Pecorelli |date= April 1999 |title=MansonWorld |journal=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] |issue=#129 |pages=44–52 }}</ref>

In a civil battery suit, David Diaz, a security officer from a concert in [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota, on October 27, 2000, sued for {{US$|75,000}} in a Minneapolis federal court.<ref>{{cite news |last = Gustafson |first= Paul |title = No verdict yet in Marilyn Manson trial |newspaper = [[Star Tribune]]  |date = September 6, 2003 |page = 9B}}</ref> The federal court jury found in Manson's favor.<ref>{{cite news |last = Smyntek |first= John |title = Names & faces |newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]] |date = September 10, 2003 |page = 2D}}</ref> In a civil suit presented by [[Oakland County]], [[Michigan]], Manson was charged with [[sexual misconduct]] against another security officer, Joshua Keasler, during a concert in [[Clarkston, Michigan]], on July 30, 2001. Oakland County originally filed assault and [[battery (crime)|battery]] and [[sexual misconduct|criminal sexual misconduct]] charges,<ref>{{cite news|author = Potts, Laura|title = Manson charged with assault|newspaper = [[South Bend Tribune]]|date = August 17, 2001|page = A2}}</ref> but the judge reduced the latter charge to misdemeanor disorderly conduct.<ref>{{cite news|title = Judge rules rocker's act not a sexual one|newspaper = [[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]
|date = January 2, 2002|page = E2}}</ref> Manson pleaded [[nolo contendere|no contest]] to the reduced charges, paid a {{US$|4,000}} fine,<ref>{{cite news|title = Marilyn Manson ordered to pay fine for assault|newspaper = [[National Post]]
|date = June 20, 2002|page = AL6}}</ref> and later settled the lawsuit under undisclosed terms.<ref>{{cite news|author = Derakhshani, Tirdad|title = Marilyn Manson gyration suit is settled|newspaper = The Philadelphia Inquirer|date = February 19, 2004|page = D2}}</ref>

On April 3, 2002, Maria St. John filed a lawsuit in Los Angeles Superior Court accusing Manson of providing her adult daughter, [[Jennifer Syme]], with [[cocaine]] and instructing her to drive while under the influence.<ref name="wrongful">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453344/20020409/story.jhtml |title=Manson May Fight Wrongful Death Suit With Countersuit |author=Vineyard, Jennifer |publisher=MTV News |date=April 9, 2002 |access-date=February 14, 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116104320/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453344/20020409/story.jhtml |archive-date=January 16, 2008 }}</ref> After attending a party at Manson's house, Syme was given a lift home;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453249/20020403/marilyn_manson.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson Accused of Contributing To Friend's Death |author=Vineyard, Jennifer |date=April 3, 2002 |work=MTV |access-date=June 14, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606154145/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453249/20020403/marilyn_manson.jhtml |archive-date=June 6, 2010 }}</ref> Manson claims she was taken home by a designated driver.<ref name=wrongful /> After she got home, she got behind the wheel of her own vehicle and was killed when she crashed it into three parked cars. Manson is reported to have said there were no alcohol or other drugs at the party; St. John's lawyer disputed this claim.<ref name=wrongful />

On August 2, 2007, former band member [[Madonna Wayne Gacy|Stephen Bier]] filed a lawsuit against Manson for unpaid "partnership proceeds", seeking $20&nbsp;million in back pay. Several details from the lawsuit leaked to the press.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=25024_0_2_0_C |title=Marilyn Manson is a fraudulent Nazi artifacts collector says former bandmember |work=SIDE-LINE.com |date=August 6, 2007 |access-date=February 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429205740/http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=25024_0_2_0_C |archive-date=April 29, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=78000 |title=Marilyn Manson Sued By Former Keyboardist/Drummer Over 'Partnership Proceeds' |publisher=BLABBERMOUTH.NET |date=August 2, 2007 |access-date=February 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302131153/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=78000 |archive-date=March 2, 2008 }}</ref> In December 2007, Manson countersued, claiming that Bier failed to fulfill his duties as a bandmember to play for recordings and to promote the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=P28015_0_2_0 |title=Marilyn Manson files countersuit against ex-bandmate Stephen Bier |work=SIDE-LINE.com |date=December 25, 2007 |access-date=February 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108013345/http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=P28015_0_2_0 |archive-date=January 8, 2009 }}</ref> On December 28, 2009, the suit was settled with an agreement which saw Bier's attorneys being paid a total of $380,000.<ref>[http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=51602 "Marilyn Manson Settles Lawsuit With Former Band Member Stephen Bier"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606025204/http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=51602 |date=June 6, 2011 }} www.metalunderground.com. Access date: February 15, 2011.</ref>

==Philanthropy==
Manson has supported various charitable causes throughout his career. In 2002, he worked with the [[Make-A-Wish Foundation]] to collaborate with a fan who had been diagnosed with a life-threatening illness. 16-year-old Andrew Baines from [[Tennessee]] was invited into the band's recording studio to record backing vocals for their then-upcoming album, ''[[The Golden Age of Grotesque]]''. Manson said on his website, "Yesterday, I spent the afternoon with Andrew, who reminded me the things I create are only made complete by those who enjoy them. I just want to simply say, thank you to Andrew for sharing such an important wish with me."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-makes-dying-fan-s-wish-come-true/ |title=Marilyn Manson Makes Dying Fan's Wish Come True |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=August 29, 2002 |access-date=October 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024025616/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-makes-dying-fan-s-wish-come-true/ |archive-date=October 24, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/marilyn-manson-shows-his-softer-side-66313.html |title=Marilyn Manson shows his softer side |work=[[Irish Examiner]] |date=August 31, 2002 |access-date=October 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024030756/http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/marilyn-manson-shows-his-softer-side-66313.html |archive-date=October 24, 2016 }}</ref> He contributed to [[Oxfam]]'s 2013 "Rumble in the Jumble" event, which raised money to aid victims of domestic and sexual abuse in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/marilyn-manson/news/celebrities-donate-items-to-charity-jumble-sale_3440561 |title=Marilyn Manson &#124; Celebrities Donate Items To Charity Jumble Sale |work=[[Contactmusic.com]] |date=January 9, 2013 |access-date=October 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024023614/http://www.contactmusic.com/marilyn-manson/news/celebrities-donate-items-to-charity-jumble-sale_3440561 |archive-date=October 24, 2016 }}</ref> He has supported various organizations – such as Music for Life and Little Kids Rock – which enable access to musical instruments and education to children of low-income families. He has also worked with Project Nightlight, a group that encourages children and teenagers to speak out against physical and sexual abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/06/marilyn-manson_n_6625118.html |title=25 Unexpected Facts About Marilyn Manson (Only One Of Which Involves Mario Kart) |author=Gasparek, Brian |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 6, 2015 |access-date=October 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819191844/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/06/marilyn-manson_n_6625118.html |archive-date=August 19, 2016 }}</ref> In 2019, he performed alongside [[Cyndi Lauper]] at her annual 'Home for the Holidays' benefit concert, with all proceeds donated to Lauper's [[True Colors United]], which "works to develop solutions to youth homelessness that focus on the unique experiences of [[LGBTQ]] young people".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/cyndi-lauper-marilyn-manson-henry-rollins-kesha-home-for-the-holidays-925373/ |title=Cyndi Lauper Duets With Marilyn Manson, Henry Rollins at Benefit Gig |author=Kreps, Daniel |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=December 11, 2019 |access-date=February 20, 2020 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223055831/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/cyndi-lauper-marilyn-manson-henry-rollins-kesha-home-for-the-holidays-925373/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/cyndi-lauper-henry-rollins-home-for-holidays-benefit-1203433598/ |title=Cyndi Lauper Punks It Up with Henry Rollins, Marilyn Manson at LGBTQ Homeless Benefit |author=Willman, Chris |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 11, 2019 |access-date=February 20, 2020 |archive-date=January 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126051438/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/cyndi-lauper-henry-rollins-home-for-holidays-benefit-1203433598/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Personal life ==

=== Relationships ===
[[File:Dita Von Teese at Cannes 2007.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Dita Von Teese]] and Manson were married from 2005 to 2007.]]

Manson is [[heterosexual]].<ref name="heterosexual">{{cite web|author-last1=Manson|author-first1=Marilyn|author-last2=King|author-first2=Larry|author2-link=Larry King|date=November 20, 2017|title=Marilyn Manson on Alice Cooper, Blame for School Shootings & Kanye West vs Jay-Z [Full Interview]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XlakLIwqfXw|access-date=September 8, 2021|time=8:40|via=[[YouTube]]|quote='''King''':You're a heterosexual? '''Manson''':Oh I'm very heterosexual|archive-date=August 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210815184156/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XlakLIwqfXw|url-status=live}}</ref> He was engaged to actress [[Rose McGowan]] from February 1999 to January 2001. McGowan later ended their engagement, citing "lifestyle differences."<ref name="abc01">{{cite web |title=Rock Romance Shocker: Manson and McGowan Split |url= https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=110753|access-date=August 12, 2017 |date= January 18, 2001|work= ABC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521140229/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=110753 |archive-date= May 21, 2014}}</ref>

Manson and [[burlesque]] dancer, model, and [[costume designer]] [[Dita Von Teese]] became a couple in 2001. He proposed on March 22, 2004, and they were married in a private, [[non-denominational]] ceremony officiated by [[Chileans|Chilean]] film director [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]].<ref>{{cite news|title=All about Alejandro|last=Braund|first=Simon|date=October 2009|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire Magazine]]|page=139}}</ref> On December 30, 2006, Von Teese filed for divorce due to "irreconcilable differences".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6236663.stm |title=Rock star Manson set to divorce |work=BBC News |date=January 6, 2007 |access-date=February 16, 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021022016/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6236663.stm |archive-date=October 21, 2007 }}</ref> Von Teese also eventually stated she did not agree with Manson's "partying or his relationship with another girl."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/main.jhtml?xml=/fashion/2007/04/22/stdita122.xml&page=3 |title=Educating Dita |work=Sunday Telegraph |date=April 22, 2007 |access-date=February 15, 2008 |location=London |first=Kimberly |last=Cutter |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209233011/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/main.jhtml?xml=%2Ffashion%2F2007%2F04%2F22%2Fstdita122.xml&page=3 |archive-date=February 9, 2008 }}</ref> Manson's "heavy [[Alcoholic drink|boozing]]" and distant behavior were also cited as cause for the split.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/features/news/2007/01/070105_marilyn/ |title=Splitsville for Marilyn Manson and Dita Von Teese |work=SPIN |date=January 5, 2007 |access-date=February 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103233017/http://www.spin.com/features/news/2007/01/070105_marilyn/ |archive-date=January 3, 2008 }}</ref> A judgment of divorce was entered in [[Los Angeles County Superior Court|Los Angeles Superior Court]] on December 27, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Entertainment/2007/12/28/manson-von_teese_marriage_ended/2173/ |title=Manson-Von Teese marriage ended |work=United Press International |date=December 28, 2007 |access-date=February 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206105331/http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Entertainment/2007/12/28/manson-von_teese_marriage_ended/2173/ |archive-date=February 6, 2008 }}</ref>

Manson's relationship with actress, model, and musician [[Evan Rachel Wood]] was made public in 2007.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Lee |first=Ken |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20007918,00.html |title=People Magazine |magazine=People |date=January 9, 2007 |access-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730111756/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20007918%2C00.html |archive-date=July 30, 2013 }}</ref> They reportedly maintained an [[on-again, off-again relationship]] for several years. He proposed to Wood during a [[Paris]] stage performance in January 2010, but the couple broke off the engagement later that year.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jennifer|last1=Garcia|first2=Jessica|last2=Herndon|title=Marilyn Manson and Evan Rachel Wood Call It Quits (Again!) |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20413552,00.html?hpt=T2 |work=People |access-date=March 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082518/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20413552%2C00.html?hpt=T2 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 }}</ref>

In the March 2012 issue of ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' magazine, American photographer Lindsay Usich was referred to as Manson's [[girlfriend]]. The article referenced a new painting by him featuring her. Usich is credited as the photo source for the cover art of Manson's 2012 album, ''[[Born Villain]]''. It was later confirmed that the two were romantically involved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/marilyn-manson-admits-wanting-children_n_1677293.html |title=Marilyn Manson Admits He Might Want To Have A Child |newspaper=The Huffington Post |date=July 16, 2012 |access-date=April 10, 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719095542/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/marilyn-manson-admits-wanting-children_n_1677293.html |archive-date=July 19, 2012 }}</ref> In February 2015, Manson told ''[[Beat Magazine|Beat]]'' magazine that he is "newly single".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.beat.com.au/music/marilyn-manson-0 | title=Marilyn Manson | work=Beat Magazine | date=February 2015 | access-date=February 25, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619221824/http://www.beat.com.au/music/marilyn-manson-0 | archive-date=June 19, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>

In October 2020, Manson revealed in an interview with [[Nicolas Cage]] on [[ABC News Radio]] that he was married in a private ceremony during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2020/10/23/marilyn-manson-reveals-hes-married-in-interview-with-nicolas.html | title=Marilyn Manson reveals he's married in interview with Nicolas Cage | publisher=ABC News Radio | date=October 2020 | access-date=November 4, 2020 | archive-date=October 31, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031102801/http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2020/10/23/marilyn-manson-reveals-hes-married-in-interview-with-nicolas.html | url-status=live }}</ref> The person he married was revealed to be Usich after she changed her social media name to "Lindsay Elizabeth Warner".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.instagram.com/lindsayusichofficial/ | title=Lindsay Elizabeth Warner | date=October 2020 | access-date=November 4, 2020}}</ref>

Manson is the godfather of [[Lily-Rose Depp]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/marilyn-manson-johnny-depp-amber-heard-divorce-he-was-completely-crucified-unjustly-a7225936.html|title=Marilyn Manson defends Johnny Depp over domestic abuse allegations|website=The Independent|access-date=August 17, 2018|archive-date=September 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924194843/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/marilyn-manson-johnny-depp-amber-heard-divorce-he-was-completely-crucified-unjustly-a7225936.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Beliefs ===
Manson claims he was a friend of [[Anton LaVey]],<ref>{{cite web| first=Chad| last=Hensley| url=http://www.esoterra.org/manson.htm| title=The Voice of Generation Hex: An interview with Marilyn Manson| work=Esoterra Magazine, The Journal of Extreme Culture| year=1996| access-date=June 18, 2016| archive-date=January 31, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131150604/http://www.esoterra.org/manson.htm| url-status=live}}</ref> and early on had also claimed LaVey inducted him as a minister in the [[Church of Satan]]. Later in his career Manson downplayed this, saying he was "not necessarily" a minister: "that was something earlier... it was a friend of mine who's now dead, who was a philosopher that I thought I learned a lot from. And that was a title I was given, so a lot of people made a lot out of it. But it's not a real job, I didn't get paid for it."<ref name="HBOMaher2003">{{Cite episode | title = Children at Risk | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsHjQaFBXWQ | via = YouTube | series = The O'Reilly Factor | credits = Presenter: [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] | network = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] | station = [[Fox News]] | location = New York| airdate = August 20, 2001 | minutes = 7:19 | transcript = Transcript | transcript-url = https://www.foxnews.com/story/marilyn-manson | access-date = May 10, 2019 | archive-date = May 29, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190529185226/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsHjQaFBXWQ&gl=US&hl=en | url-status = live }}</ref> The Church of Satan itself later confirmed Manson was never ordained as a minister in their church.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/church-satan-clarifies-marilyn-mansons-role-2370035 |title=The Church Of Satan clarifies Marilyn Manson's role |first=Andrew |last=Trendell |work=[[NME]] |date=August 23, 2018 |access-date=December 4, 2020 |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109010133/https://www.nme.com/news/music/church-satan-clarifies-marilyn-mansons-role-2370035 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Despite that, Manson has been described as "the highest profile Satanist ever" with strong [[anti-Christian]] views and [[social Darwinist]] leanings.<ref>{{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mathews|title=Modern Satanism: Anatomy of a Radical Subculture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mQrbsOWaOyUC|year=2009|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|location=Westport, Connecticut|isbn=978-0-313-36639-0|access-date=January 16, 2018|archive-date=December 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213171232/https://books.google.com/books?id=mQrbsOWaOyUC|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Manson denies this, and stated the following:

{{cquote|"I'm not a misanthrope. I'm not a [[nihilist]]. I'm not an [[atheist]]. I believe in spirituality, but it really has to come from somewhere else. I learned a long time ago, you can't try to change the world, you can just try to make something in it. I think that's my spirituality, it's putting something into the world. If you take all the basic principles of any religion, it's usually about creation. There's also destruction, but creation essentially. I was raised Christian. I went to a Christian school, because my parents wanted me to get a better education. But when I got kicked out I was sent to public school, and got beat up more by the public school kids. But then I'd go to my friend's [[Passover]] and have fun."|author=Marilyn Manson<ref>{{cite interview |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XlakLIwqfXw |title=Marilyn Manson on Alice Cooper, Blame for School Shootings & Kanye West vs Jay-Z [Full Interview] |subject=Marilyn Manson |interviewer=[[Larry King]] |access-date=May 10, 2019 |via=YouTube |archive-date=May 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529185228/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XlakLIwqfXw&gl=US&hl=en |url-status=live }}</ref>}}

Manson is also familiar with the writings of [[Aleister Crowley]] and [[Friedrich Nietzsche]]. He quotes Crowley throughout his autobiography, including [[Thelema]]'s principal dictum, "Do what thou wilt shall be the whole of the Law."<ref>{{cite news|first=Glenn|last=Minnis|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/swiss-dont-dig-mansons-act/|title=Swiss Don't Dig Manson's Act|website=[[CBS]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 2, 2003|access-date=June 18, 2016|archive-date=August 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820182806/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/swiss-dont-dig-mansons-act/|url-status=live}}</ref> Crowley's esoteric subject matter forms an important theme in much of Manson's early work.<ref>{{cite web| first=Nick| last=Kushner| url=http://www.nachtkabarett.com/theOccult/AleisterCrowley| title=Aleister Crowley| access-date=September 2, 2016| archive-date=December 15, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215092701/http://www.nachtkabarett.com/theOccult/AleisterCrowley| url-status=live}}</ref>

==Controversies==
Marilyn Manson has been referred to as one of the most iconic and controversial figures in [[heavy metal music]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://teamrock.com/feature/2015-01-14/the-a-z-of-marilyn-manson|title=The A-Z Of Marilyn Manson – Feature|author=Lloyd, Gavin|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|date=January 14, 2015|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812155024/http://teamrock.com/feature/2015-01-14/the-a-z-of-marilyn-manson|archive-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/06/marilyn-manson_n_6625118.html|title=25 Unexpected Facts About Marilyn Manson (Only One Of Which Involves Mario Kart)|author=Gasparek, Brian|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=February 6, 2015|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819191844/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/06/marilyn-manson_n_6625118.html|archive-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://noisecreep.com/best-marilyn-manson-videos/|title=10 Best Marilyn Manson Videos|author=Ford, Chris|work=[[Noisecreep]]|date=January 3, 2014|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103222207/http://noisecreep.com/best-marilyn-manson-videos/|archive-date=November 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3344860/worst-best-music-videos-marilyn-manson/|title=[From Worst To Best&#93; The Music Videos Of Marilyn Manson|author=Barkan, Jonathan|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=May 13, 2015|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008154642/http://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3344860/worst-best-music-videos-marilyn-manson/|archive-date=October 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/outrage-watch-marilyn-manson-is-playing-a-native-american-ya-think-therell-be-backlash|title=Outrage Watch: Johnny Depp can probably relate to this Marilyn Manson controversy|author=Eggertsen, Chris|work=[[HitFix]]|date=August 12, 2015|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815192949/http://www.hitfix.com/news/outrage-watch-marilyn-manson-is-playing-a-native-american-ya-think-therell-be-backlash|archive-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref> with some referring to him as a "[[Popular culture|pop culture]] [[Cultural icon|icon]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/music/the-1997-edition-was-the-best-mtv-video-music-awards-2405739|title=The 1997 Edition Was the Best MTV Video Music Awards|author=Chaz, Kangas|work=[[LA Weekly]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=September 6, 2012|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102134726/http://www.laweekly.com/music/the-1997-edition-was-the-best-mtv-video-music-awards-2405739|archive-date=January 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/31647/1/marc-jacobs-casts-marilyn-manson-and-courtney-love-aw16-ad|title=Marc Jacobs casts Marilyn Manson and Courtney Love in new ad|author=DeWolf, Anna|magazine=[[Dazed Digital]]|publisher=[[Dazed]]|date=June 20, 2016|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726102507/http://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/31647/1/marc-jacobs-casts-marilyn-manson-and-courtney-love-aw16-ad|archive-date=July 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/read-serial-killer-charles-mansons-batshit-insane-letter-marilyn-manson/|title=Read Charles Manson's Batshit Insane Letter To Marilyn Manson|author=Mack, Emmy|magazine=[[Music Feeds]]|date=December 23, 2015|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221154537/http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/read-serial-killer-charles-mansons-batshit-insane-letter-marilyn-manson/|archive-date=February 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/entertainment/editorial/news/160105-46-years-marilyn-manson-has-society-finally|title=47 years of Marilyn Manson: Has society finally understood him?|work=[[Times Music|RadioandMusic.com]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|date=January 5, 2016|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817152643/http://www.radioandmusic.com/entertainment/editorial/news/160105-46-years-marilyn-manson-has-society-finally|archive-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' magazine said there were "few artists in the 90s as shocking as Marilyn Manson, the most famous of the [[Shock rock|shock-rockers]]".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/10/13-scariest-musicians.html|title=The 13 Scariest Bands of All Time|author=Bonaime, Ross|magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=October 31, 2011|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817133157/https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/10/13-scariest-musicians.html|archive-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> In her book ''Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories That Shaped Our Culture'', author Jacqueline Edmondson writes that Manson creates music that "challenges people's worldviews and provokes questions and further thinking".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA291|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories That Shaped Our Culture|page=291|author=Edmondson, Jacqueline|publisher=[[ABC-Clio]]|date=October 3, 2013|isbn=9780313393488 |access-date=March 18, 2022}}</ref> Manson, his work, and the work of his eponymous band, have been involved in numerous controversies throughout their career.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://journals.openedition.org/ejas/pdf/12098 |title="I Am Your Faggot Anti-Pope": An Exploration of Marilyn Manson as a Transgressive Artist |first=Coco|last=d'Hont|journal=[[Journal of American Studies|European Journal of American Studies]] |publisher=[[Centre pour l'Édition Électronique Ouverte]] |date=Summer 2017 |access-date=June 23, 2020 |pages=1–17 |issn=1991-9336 |others=[[Directory of Open Access Journals]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623135154/https://journals.openedition.org/ejas/pdf/12098 |archive-date=June 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RReDDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA67|title=Metal Music: A History for Headbangers|pages=67–69|author=Horning, Nicole|publisher=[[Greenhaven Press]]|date=December 15, 2018|isbn=9781534565265 |access-date=March 18, 2022}}</ref>

On May 30, 1996, the co-directors of political [[advocacy group]] [[FreedomWorks|Empower America]] organized a [[bipartisan]] press conference with [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[William Bennett]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]s [[Joe Lieberman|Joseph Lieberman]] and [[C. Delores Tucker]], in which the [[record industry]] was admonished for selling "prepackaged, shrink-wrapped [[nihilism]]." The three largely targeted rap music, but also referenced Manson; Tucker called ''Smells Like Children'' the "dirtiest, nastiest porno record directed at children that has ever hit the market" and said distributing record labels had "the blood of children on their hands", while Lieberman said the music "celebrates some of the most antisocial and immoral behaviors imaginable." They also announced that Empower America would be launching a $25,000 radio advertising campaign to collect petitions from listeners who wanted record companies to "stop spreading this vicious, vulgar music."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/507687/elvis-fan-bill-bennett-attacks-rap-marilyn-manson/|title=Elvis Fan Bill Bennett Attacks Rap, Marilyn Manson|author-link=Michael Goldberg (writer)|author=Goldberg, Michael|work=MTV|publisher=Viacom Media Network|date=June 1, 1996|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809201001/http://www.mtv.com/news/507687/elvis-fan-bill-bennett-attacks-rap-marilyn-manson/|archive-date=August 9, 2016}}</ref>

The release of ''Antichrist Superstar'' in 1996 coincided with the band's commercial breakthrough,<ref name="Destroyed">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/sep/21/columbine-destroyed-my-entire-career-marilyn-manson-on-the-perils-of-being-the-lord-of-darkness|title='Columbine destroyed my entire career': Marilyn Manson on the perils of being the lord of darkness|author-link=Alexis Petridis|author=Petridis, Alexis|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=September 21, 2017|access-date=April 25, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807113346/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/sep/21/columbine-destroyed-my-entire-career-marilyn-manson-on-the-perils-of-being-the-lord-of-darkness|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and much of the attention received by Manson from mainstream media was not positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-antichrist-superstar-album-anniversary/|title=24 Years Ago: Marilyn Manson Makes Creative Leap With 'Antichrist Superstar'|last=Childers|first=Chad|work=[[Loudwire]]|date=October 8, 2016|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429062130/http://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-antichrist-superstar-album-anniversary/|archive-date=April 29, 2017}}</ref> Empower America organized another press conference in December 1996, where they criticized [[MCA Records|MCA]]&mdash;the owner of Interscope&mdash;president [[Edgar Bronfman Jr.]] for profiting from "profanity-laced" albums by Manson, [[Tupac Shakur]] and [[Snoop Dogg|Snoop Doggy Dogg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/508715/another-right-wing-attack-on-rap-rock/ |title=Another Right Wing Attack On Rap & Rock |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |publisher=MTV |date=December 11, 1996 |access-date=January 13, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113150720/http://www.mtv.com/news/508715/another-right-wing-attack-on-rap-rock/ |archive-date=January 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-mcaphilips10dec1096-story.html |title=Critics expected to take on MCA for explicit rap lyrics |author-link=Chuck Philips |author=Philips, Chuck |work=Los Angeles Times |date=December 10, 1996 |access-date=May 31, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513090752/http://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-mcaphilips10dec1096-story.html |archive-date=May 13, 2016}}</ref> The band's live performances also came under fire during this period; the "Dead to the World Tour" was followed by protesters at nearly every North American venue it visited.<ref name="Traveling">{{cite web|url=https://partners.nytimes.com/library/cyber/mirapaul/042497mirapaul.html|title=The Traveling Controversy That Is Marilyn Manson|author=Mirapaul, Matthew|work=The New York Times|date=April 24, 1997|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008154435/https://partners.nytimes.com/library/cyber/mirapaul/042497mirapaul.html|archive-date=October 8, 2016}}</ref> Opponents of the band claimed the shows featured elements of [[Satanism]], including a satanic [[altar]], [[bestiality]], rape, the distribution of free drugs,<ref name="Destroyed"/> homosexual acts, as well as [[Animal sacrifice|animal]] and even [[human sacrifice]]s.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-the-vampire-of-the-hollywood-hills-241042/|title=Marilyn Manson: The Vampire of the Hollywood Hills |author=Hedegaard, Erik |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=January 6, 2015 |access-date=January 24, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203154420/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-the-vampire-of-the-hollywood-hills-241042/|archive-date=February 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Anonymous [[affidavit]]s compiled by the [[Gulf Coast of the United States|Gulf Coast]] division of the [[American Family Association]] made various other claims about the live shows.<ref name="Traveling"/> Students in Florida were threatened with expulsion for attending the band's concerts.<ref name="Destroyed"/>

Several [[State legislature (United States)|state legislatures]], including the [[Utah State Legislature]], [[South Carolina Legislature]] and the [[Virginia General Assembly]], enacted legislation specifically targeting the group, banning them from performing at [[State ownership|state-operated]] venues.<ref name="UtahFans">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/493/marilyn-manson-fans-settle-lawsuit-over-canceled-utah-show/|title=Marilyn Manson Fans Settle Lawsuit Over Canceled Utah Show|work=[[MTV News]]|date=June 24, 1997|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616223537/http://www.mtv.com/news/493/marilyn-manson-fans-settle-lawsuit-over-canceled-utah-show/|archive-date=June 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/1997-04-20/news/9704200018_1_marilyn-manson-brian-warner-live-crew|title=Richmond Makes Martyr Out Of Manson|author=Spencer, Jim|work=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|date=April 20, 1997|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804045036/http://articles.dailypress.com/1997-04-20/news/9704200018_1_marilyn-manson-brian-warner-live-crew|archive-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name="ACLUozzy">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/509481/ozzy-to-sue-new-jersey-over-marilyn-manson/|title=Ozzy Osbourne To Sue New Jersey Over Marilyn Manson|author=Nelson, Chris|work=[[MTV News]]|date=April 19, 1997|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616220503/http://www.mtv.com/news/509481/ozzy-to-sue-new-jersey-over-marilyn-manson/|archive-date=June 16, 2016}}</ref> These laws would later be repealed, following separate lawsuits from fans and the [[American Civil Liberties Union]].<ref name="UtahFans"/><ref name="ACLUozzy"/> [[Ozzy Osbourne]] sued the [[New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority]] after they forced the cancelation of the New Jersey date of the [[Ozzfest (1997)|1997 Ozzfest]] at [[Giants Stadium]]; Manson's appearance had been cited as the reason for the cancelation.<ref name="ACLUozzy"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/06/17/arts/heavy-metal-upstaged-by-a-fury-offstage.html|title=Heavy Metal Upstaged By a Fury Offstage|author=Strauss, Neil|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 17, 1997|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701113155/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/06/17/arts/heavy-metal-upstaged-by-a-fury-offstage.html|archive-date=July 1, 2016|author-link=Neil Strauss}}</ref> In November 1997, Manson's lyrical content was examined during [[United States congressional hearing|congressional hearings]] led by Lieberman and [[Sam Brownback]], in an attempt to determine the effects&mdash;if any&mdash;of violent lyrics on young listeners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/1997/11/blaming-shock-rockers |title=Blaming the Shock Rockers: Now that Frank Zappa's dead, who will stick up for Marilyn Manson? |last=Kretkowski |first=Paul D. |work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] |date=November 11, 1997 |access-date=March 31, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408023514/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/1997/11/blaming-shock-rockers |archive-date=April 8, 2016}}</ref> The subcommittee heard testimony from Raymond Kuntz, who blamed his son's suicide on ''Antichrist Superstar''—specifically the song "The Reflecting God".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1775/senate-hearing-attempts-to-connect-manson-to-suicide/ |title=Senate Hearing Attempts To Connect Manson To Suicide |last=Nelson |first= Chris |work=MTV News |date=November 7, 1997|access-date=August 6, 2016|url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809203232/http://www.mtv.com/news/1775/senate-hearing-attempts-to-connect-manson-to-suicide/ |archive-date=August 9, 2016}}</ref> Lieberman went on to claim that the band's music was driving young listeners to commit suicide,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/01/21/marilyn-manson-on-charlie-hebdo-and-why-you-should-avoid-foursomes.html|title=Marilyndest Manson on Charlie Hebdo and Why You Should Avoid Foursomes|author=Stern, Marlow|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=January 21, 2015|access-date=April 26, 2022|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705034949/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/01/21/marilyn-manson-on-charlie-hebdo-and-why-you-should-avoid-foursomes.html|archivedate=July 5, 2016 }}</ref> and called the band the "sickest group ever promoted by a mainstream record company."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/17/arts/a-bogey-band-to-scare-parents-with.html|title=A Bogey Band to Scare Parents With|author=Strauss, Neil|work=The New York Times|date=May 17, 1997|access-date=March 31, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306175217/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/17/arts/a-bogey-band-to-scare-parents-with.html|archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref>

===Columbine High School massacre===
{{main article|Marilyn Manson–Columbine High School massacre controversy}}
On April 20, 1999, [[Columbine High School]] students [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]] killed thirteen people and wounded twenty-one others before committing suicide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/justice/2012/12/14/1337221/a-timeline-of-mass-shootings-in-the-us-since-columbine/ |title=A Timeline Of Mass Shootings In The US Since Columbine |author=Aviva Shen |website=[[ThinkProgress]] |date=December 14, 2012 |access-date=April 27, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430004241/http://thinkprogress.org/justice/2012/12/14/1337221/a-timeline-of-mass-shootings-in-the-us-since-columbine/ |archive-date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> At the time, it was the [[List of school shootings in the United States by death toll|deadliest school shooting in US history]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.history.com/topics/1990s/columbine-high-school-shootings|title=Columbine High School Shooting: Victims & Killers|work=[[History.com]]|date=November 9, 2009|access-date=April 22, 2022}}</ref> In the immediate aftermath of [[Columbine High School massacre|the massacre]], media reports surfaced that were heavily critical of [[Goth subculture]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2019/04/19/bullies-black-trench-coats-columbine-shootings-most-dangerous-myths/|title=Bullies and black trench coats: The Columbine shooting's most dangerous myths|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Brockell, Gillian|date=April 20, 2019|access-date=April 23, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/apr/22/stuartmillar1|title=A clique within a clique, obsessed with guns, death and Hitler|author1=Wright, Gerard|author2=Millar, Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 22, 1999|access-date=April 22, 2022}}</ref> alleging the perpetrators were wearing Marilyn Manson T-shirts during the massacre,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/columbine-how-marilyn-manson-became-mainstream-medias-scapegoat|title=Columbine: How Marilyn Manson Became Mainstream Media's Scapegoat|author=Brannigan, Paul|work=[[Kerrang!]]|date=April 20, 2019|access-date=April 25, 2022}}</ref> and that they were influenced by violence in entertainment, specifically movies, video games and music.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/25/weekinreview/the-nation-the-stresses-of-youth-the-strains-of-its-music.html|title=The Nation; The Stresses of Youth, The Strains of Its Music|author-link=Anne Powers|author=Powers, Ann|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 25, 2000|access-date=April 25, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518070833/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/25/weekinreview/the-nation-the-stresses-of-youth-the-strains-of-its-music.html|archive-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref> Five days after the incident, William Bennet and Joseph Lieberman – longtime critics of the vocalist – appeared on ''[[Meet the Press]]'', where they cited his music as a contributing factor to the shooting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/513754/colorado-tragedy-continues-to-spark-manson-bashing/|title=Colorado Tragedy Continues To Spark Manson Bashing|author=O'Connor, Christopher|work=[[MTV]]|date=April 26, 1999|access-date=June 1, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610112300/http://www.mtv.com/news/513754/colorado-tragedy-continues-to-spark-manson-bashing/|archive-date=June 10, 2016}}</ref> Soon after, [[Sensationalism|sensationalist]] headlines such as "Killers Worshipped Rock Freak Manson" and "Devil-Worshipping Maniac Told Kids To Kill" began appearing in media coverage of the tragedy.<ref name="Screaming">{{cite magazine|author=Tom Bryant |date=November 10, 2010 |title=Screaming For Vengeance |magazine=[[Kerrang!]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |pages=40–42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Jones, Steve|editor=Baker, Susan|title=Pop Music and the Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N-ViwZnnR3oC|access-date=April 22, 2022|year=2002|publisher=[[Temple University Press]]|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-1-56639-966-1|pages=126–127}}</ref> Despite confirmation that the pair were fans of German [[Industrial music|industrial]] bands such as [[KMFDM]] and [[Rammstein]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revolvermag.com/music/marilyn-mansons-holy-wood-10-things-you-didnt-know-2000s-lp-fight-songs|title=Marilyn Manson's 'Holy Wood': 10 Things You Didn't Know About 2000's LP of Fight Songs|author=Weiderhorn, Jon|work=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]|date=November 12, 2018|access-date=April 22, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://denver.rockymountainnews.com/shooting/0822fata1.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010221031521/http://denver.rockymountainnews.com/shooting/0822fata1.shtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=2001-02-21|title=Fatal Friendship|author1=Bartels, Lynn|author2=Crowder, Carla|work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|date=August 22, 1999|access-date=April 22, 2022}}</ref> and had "nothing but contempt" for Manson's music,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/|title=Inside the Columbine High investigation|author=Cullen, Dave|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=September 23, 1999|access-date=April 22, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517044320/http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/|archive-date=May 17, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> mainstream media continued to direct the [[Marilyn Manson–Columbine High School massacre controversy|majority of blame for the shooting at Manson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=
https://loudwire.com/rock-music-demonized-by-mainstream/|title=10 Times Rock Music Was Demonized by the Mainstream|author=Blum, Jordan|work=[[Loudwire]]|date=July 14, 2021|access-date=April 22, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/04/20/columbine.pop.culture/index.html|title=Columbine left its indelible mark on pop culture|author=France, Lisa Respers|work=[[CNN]]|date=April 20, 2009|access-date=April 27, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422164650/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/04/20/columbine.pop.culture/index.html|archive-date=April 22, 2009}}</ref>

The [[List of mayors of Denver|Mayor of Denver]], [[Wellington Webb]], successfully petitioned for the cancelation of [[KBPI|KBPI-FM]]'s annual "Birthday Bash", at which Manson was scheduled to appear on April 30. Webb said the concert would be "inappropriate" because the two gunmen were fans of Marilyn Manson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1427257/marilyn-manson-concert-other-denver-events-cancelled-in-wake-of-high-school-shooting/|title=Marilyn Manson Concert, Other Denver Events Cancelled In Wake Of High School Shooting|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]]|date=April 22, 1999 |access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425020136/http://www.mtv.com/news/1427257/marilyn-manson-concert-other-denver-events-cancelled-in-wake-of-high-school-shooting/|archive-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> [[Colorado]]an politicians [[Bill Owens (Colorado politician)|Bill Owens]] and [[Tom Tancredo]] accused Manson of promoting "hate, violence, death, suicide, drug use and the attitudes and actions of the Columbine High School killers."<ref name="ColoradoGovernor">{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1443825/colorado-governor-congressman-support-anti-manson-group/ |title=Colorado Governor, Congressman Support Anti-Manson Group |first=Joe |last=D'Angelo |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=May 21, 2001 |access-date=April 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425024741/http://www.mtv.com/news/1443825/colorado-governor-congressman-support-anti-manson-group/ |archive-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> On April 29, ten US senators led by Brownback sent a letter to the head of [[Seagram]], the [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] which owned Manson's record label, requesting they stop distributing music to children that "glorifies violence". The letter named Manson, accusing him of producing songs that "eerily reflect" the actions of Harris and Klebold.<ref>{{cite web |author=O'Connor, Christopher |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/513908/politicians-go-on-offensive-against-marilyn-manson/ |title=Politicians Go on Offensive Against Marilyn Manson |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=May 1, 1999 |access-date=May 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519175541/http://www.mtv.com/news/513908/politicians-go-on-offensive-against-marilyn-manson/ |archive-date=May 19, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Manson canceled the final four dates of the Rock Is Dead Tour out of respect for the victims while criticizing the media for their irresponsible coverage of the tragedy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/29/us/terror-in-littleton-the-culture-rock-concerts-are-cancelled.html|title=Terror in Littleton: The Culture; Rock Concerts Are Cancelled|author=Sterngold, James|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 29, 1999|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328174410/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/29/us/terror-in-littleton-the-culture-rock-concerts-are-cancelled.html|archive-date=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/331363.stm|title=Manson cancels rest of US tour|work=[[BBC News]]|date=April 29, 1999|access-date=April 25, 2022|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415123212/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/331363.stm|archive-date=April 15, 2016}}</ref> He elaborated on this point in an [[op-ed]] written for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' titled "Columbine: Whose Fault Is It?". In the article, Manson castigated [[Gun culture in the United States|America's gun culture]] and the political influence of the [[National Rifle Association]], but was heavily critical of [[news media]]. He argued the media should be blamed for the next school shooting, as it was them who propagated the ensuing hysteria and "witch hunt", and said that instead of debating more relevant societal issues, the media instead facilitated the placing of blame on a [[scapegoat]].<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Manson, Manson|title=Columbine: Whose Fault Is It?|magazine=Rolling Stone|issue=815|date=June 24, 1999|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/columbine-whose-fault-is-it-19990624|access-date=April 10, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721192522/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/columbine-whose-fault-is-it-19990624|archive-date=July 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nme.com/news/nme/1434 |title=Marilyn Manson: The Write To Be Wrong |first=Adam |last=Bychawski |work=[[NME]] |publisher=[[Time Inc. UK]] |date=May 1, 1999 |access-date=April 23, 2022 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119100905/http://www.nme.com/news/nme/1434 |archive-date=January 19, 2012}}</ref>

On May 4, Brownback chaired a congressional hearing of the [[United States Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation]] on the distribution and marketing of supposedly violent content to children by the film, music, television and video-game industries. The committee heard testimony from Bennett, the Archbishop of Denver [[Charles J. Chaput]], as well as professors and mental health professionals; they criticized Manson, his label mates Nine Inch Nails, and the 1999 film ''[[The Matrix]]'' for their alleged contribution to a cultural environment enabling violence such as the Columbine shootings. [[Recording Industry Association of America]] executive [[Hilary Rosen]] said she refused to participate in the hearing as it was "staged as [[Political posturing|political theater]]. They just wanted to find a way to shame the industry, and I'm not ashamed."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513971/19990504/index.jhtml|title=Senators Criticize Marilyn Manson, Nine Inch Nails at Hearing|author=O'Connor, Christopher|work=[[VH1]]|date=May 4, 1999|access-date=April 26, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411233607/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513971/19990504/index.jhtml|archive-date=April 11, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The committee eventually requested the [[Federal Trade Commission]] and the [[United States Department of Justice]] investigate the entertainment industry's marketing practices to minors.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tapper |first=Jake |url=http://www.salon.com/2000/08/29/hollywood_2/ |title=Hollywood on trial |work=Salon |publisher=Salon Media Group Inc. |date=August 29, 2000 |access-date=May 15, 2012}}</ref> The lyrical content of the band's 2000 album ''Holy Wood (In the Shadow of the Valley of Death)'' was largely inspired by the massacre, with Manson saying it was a rebuttal to the accusations leveled against him by mainstream media.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Tom|last=Bryant |date=November 10, 2010 |title=Screaming For Vengeance |magazine=[[Kerrang!]] |issue=1338 |pages=40–42 |issn=0262-6624}}</ref> He also discussed the massacre and its aftermath in [[Michael Moore]]'s 2002 documentary ''[[Bowling for Columbine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2007/05/cover-marilyn-manson/|title=On the Cover: Marilyn Manson|author=Ames, Jonathan|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=May 17, 2007|access-date=April 22, 2022|issn=0886-3032|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119044303/https://www.spin.com/2007/05/cover-marilyn-manson/|archive-date=January 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Other alleged incidents===
In 2000, an elderly nun was murdered by three schoolgirls in Italy, with their diaries reportedly containing numerous references to and pictures of Manson.<ref name="Innocent">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/jan/25/popandrock|title=Marilyn Manson is innocent|author=Pidd, Helen|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 5, 2005|access-date=April 23, 2022}}</ref> Soon after, he was arrested following a concert in [[Rome]] for [[allegedly]] "tearing off his genitals".<ref name="Innocent"/> Manson said the arrest was politically motivated following his implication in the murder by Italian [[Tabloid journalism|tabloid]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/marilyn-manson-268-1392720|title=Maz's Arresting Comments|work=NME|date=February 21, 2001|access-date=April 22, 2022}}</ref> In 2003, French media{{Which|date=July 2021}} blamed Manson when several teenagers vandalized the graves of British war heroes in [[Arras]], [[France]].<ref name="Innocent"/>

On June 30, 2003, 14-year old schoolgirl [[Murder of Jodi Jones|Jodi Jones]] was brutally murdered in [[Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/may/16/scotland.ukcrime |title=Luke Mitchell loses appeal in Jodi Jones murder |author=Glendinning, Lee |work=[[The Guardian]]  |date=May 16, 2008 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920133523/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/may/16/scotland.ukcrime |archive-date=September 20, 2016}}</ref> Her mutilated body was discovered in woodland near her home, with her injuries said to closely resemble those of Elizabeth Short, commonly referred to by media as the [[Black Dahlia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1480608/Jodi-Jones-death-similar-to-Hollywood-killing.html |title=Jodi Jones death 'similar to Hollywood killing' |author=Cramb, Auslan |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=January 7, 2005 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706190133/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1480608/Jodi-Jones-death-similar-to-Hollywood-killing.html |archive-date=July 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/teenager-convicted-of-jodi-murder-487597.html |title=Teenager convicted of Jodi murder &#124; Crime &#124; News |author=PA |work=[[The Independent]] |date=January 21, 2005|access-date=August 20, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829010106/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/teenager-convicted-of-jodi-murder-487597.html|archive-date=August 29, 2016}}</ref> Ten months later, Jones's boyfriend Luke Mitchell, then-fifteen years old, was arrested on suspicion of her murder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/4187007.stm |title=UK &#124; Scotland &#124; Killer 'obsessed by occult' |work=[[BBC News]] |date=January 21, 2005 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919120240/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/4187007.stm |archive-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> Police confiscated a copy of ''The Golden Age of Grotesque'' containing the short film ''Doppelherz'' during a search of Mitchell's family home,<ref name="DVD">{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/18833 |title=Marilyn Manson DVD Played In Murder Trial |author=Bychawski, Adam |work=[[NME]] |publisher=[[Time Inc. UK]] |date=December 24, 2004 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828051429/http://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/18833 |archive-date=August 28, 2016}}</ref> which had been purchased by Mitchell two days after Jones's death.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1481752/Jodi-killed-by-boyfriend-attracted-to-sex-drugs-and-Satan.html |title=Jodi killed by boyfriend attracted to sex, drugs and Satan |author=Peterkin, Tom |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]  |date=January 22, 2005 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706205247/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1481752/Jodi-killed-by-boyfriend-attracted-to-sex-drugs-and-Satan.html |archive-date=July 6, 2016}}</ref> A ten-minute excerpt from the film, as well as several paintings created by Manson depicting the Black Dahlia's mutilated body, were presented as evidence during the trial.<ref name="DVD"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/music/i-did-not-inspire-jodi-s-killer-says-rock-star-marilyn-manson-1-736017 |title=I did not inspire Jodi's killer, says rock star Marilyn Manson |work=[[The Scotsman]] |publisher=[[Johnston Press]] |date=February 14, 2005 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827200649/http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/music/i-did-not-inspire-jodi-s-killer-says-rock-star-marilyn-manson-1-736017 |archive-date=August 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/World/Blame-Jodi-killers-upbringing-Manson/2005/02/13/1108229858731.html |title=Blame Jodi killer's upbringing: Manson |author=PA |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |date=February 14, 2005 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012224209/http://www.smh.com.au/news/World/Blame-Jodi-killers-upbringing-Manson/2005/02/13/1108229858731.html |archive-date=October 12, 2016}}</ref> Mitchell was found guilty of her murder and was sentenced to a minimum of twenty years in prison.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stv.tv/news/east-central/243743-murderer-luke-mitchell-has-another-appeal-refused/ |title=Murderer Luke Mitchell has latest appeal over Jodi Jones conviction rejected |work=[[STV (TV channel)|STV]] |publisher=[[STV Group (Scotland)|STV Group]] |date=April 15, 2011 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820201727/http://stv.tv/news/east-central/243743-murderer-luke-mitchell-has-another-appeal-refused/ |archive-date=August 20, 2016}}</ref> In his closing summation, [[William Nimmo Smith, Lord Nimmo Smith|Lord Nimmo Smith]] said he believed Mitchell "carried an image of [Manson's] paintings in your memory when you killed Jodi."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/feb/12/ukcrime.kirstyscott |title=Jodi's killer to serve at least 20 years in jail &#124; UK news |author=Scott, Kirsty |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=February 12, 2005 |access-date=August 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920115635/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/feb/12/ukcrime.kirstyscott |archive-date=September 20, 2016}}</ref> Mitchell continues to profess his innocence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/crime/former-detectives-claim-police-blunders-prove-jodi-jones-murderer-luke-mitchell-is-innocent-in-new-channel-5-documentary-3142330|title=Former detectives claim police 'blunders' prove Jodi Jones murderer Luke Mitchell is innocent in new Channel 5 documentary|author=McKenzie, Jamie|work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]]|publisher=[[The Scotsman]]|date=February 22, 2021|access-date=April 23, 2022}}</ref>

The controversy connecting Manson to school shootings continued on October 10, 2007, when fourteen-year old Asa Coon [[SuccessTech Academy shooting|shot four people]] at [[SuccessTech Academy]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]], before committing suicide.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/boy-14-kills-himself-after-shooting-four-in-school-rampage-396578.html |title=Boy, 14, kills himself after shooting four in school rampage |author=Gumbel, Andrew |work=[[The Independent]]  |date=October 10, 2007 |access-date=June 2, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806161116/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/boy-14-kills-himself-after-shooting-four-in-school-rampage-396578.html |archive-date=August 6, 2016}}</ref> While exiting a bathroom, Coon was punched in the face by another student, and responded by shooting his attacker in the abdomen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/21224357/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/police-suspended-boy-shoots-ohio-school/ |title=Police: Suspended boy shoots 4 at Ohio school |work=[[NBCNews.com]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal]] |date=October 10, 2007 |access-date=June 2, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314061642/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21224357/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/police-suspended-boy-shoots-ohio-school/ |archive-date=March 14, 2016}}</ref> Coon then walked down the hallway and shot in to two occupied classrooms – wounding two teachers and a student – before entering a bathroom and committing suicide.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/US/10/10/cleveland.shooting/ |title=Police chief: Teen shoots four, kills self at Cleveland high school |work=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[Time Warner]] |date=October 11, 2007 |access-date=June 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807065243/http://edition.cnn.com/2007/US/10/10/cleveland.shooting/ |archive-date=August 7, 2016}}</ref> Coon was wearing a Marilyn Manson T-shirt during the shooting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/shooting-spree-at-cleveland-high-school/ |title=Shooting Spree At Cleveland High School |work=[[CBS News]] |publisher=[[CBS Corporation]] |date=October 10, 2007 |access-date=June 2, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629180354/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/shooting-spree-at-cleveland-high-school/ |archive-date=June 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1571704/cleveland-school-shooter-fit-sadly-predictable-profile-bullied-loner-from-troubled-home/ |title=Cleveland School Shooter Fit Sadly Predictable Profile: Bullied Loner From Troubled Home |author=Kaufman, Gil |work=[[MTV News]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005–present)|Viacom]] |date=October 11, 2007 |access-date=June 2, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616223547/http://www.mtv.com/news/1571704/cleveland-school-shooter-fit-sadly-predictable-profile-bullied-loner-from-troubled-home/ |archive-date=June 16, 2016}}</ref> A photograph of Coon's dead body was circulated online by Cleveland police officer Walter Emerick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/schoolshooting/2007/10/photo_of_asa_coons_body_taken.html|title=Photo of Asa Coon's body taken by Cleveland policeman|author=Puente, Mark|work=[[The Plain Dealer]]|publisher=[[Cleveland.com]]|date=October 20, 2007|access-date=April 24, 2022}}</ref> On May 18, 2009, Justin Doucet, a fifteen-year-old student at [[Lafourche Parish Public Schools|Larose-Cut Off Middle School]] in [[Lafourche Parish, Louisiana]], entered the school with a [[semi-automatic pistol]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2009-05-18-school-shooting-louisiana_N.htm |title=La. student shoots self, misses teacher|author=Jervis, Rick|work=[[USA Today]]|date=May 18, 2009|access-date=June 2, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818135617/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2009-05-18-school-shooting-louisiana_N.htm|archive-date=August 18, 2016}}</ref> After a teacher refused to comply with Doucet's demand to say "Hail Marilyn Manson", he fired two shots that narrowly missed the teacher's head, before shooting himself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2009/05/19/eighth-grader-attempts-suicide-after-marilyn-manson-related-altercation-with-teacher|title=Eighth Grader Attempts Suicide After Marilyn Manson-Related Altercation With Teacher|author=Hernandez, Jenn|work=[[The Fader]]|date=May 19, 2009|access-date=June 2, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815231838/http://www.thefader.com/2009/05/19/eighth-grader-attempts-suicide-after-marilyn-manson-related-altercation-with-teacher|archive-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2009/05/teen-classroom-shooter-hail-marilyn-manson/|title=Teen Classroom Shooter: 'Hail Marilyn Manson'|author=Fitzmaurice, Larry|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=May 19, 2009|access-date=June 2, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610150257/http://www.spin.com/2009/05/teen-classroom-shooter-hail-marilyn-manson/|archive-date=June 10, 2016}}</ref> Doucet died from his injuries a week later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-fan-who-shot-himself-after-firing-at-teacher-dies/ |title=Marilyn Manson Fan Who Shot Himself After Firing At Teacher Dies |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=May 25, 2009 |access-date=June 2, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805103142/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-fan-who-shot-himself-after-firing-at-teacher-dies/ |archive-date=August 5, 2016}}</ref>

===Abuse allegations===
Several of Manson's former acquaintances began communicating with one another in September 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/marilyn-manson-victims-found-healing-through-bonding/|title=Marilyn Manson's Alleged Victims Found Healing by Bonding: 'Cathartic'|author=Mier, Tomás|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=May 6, 2021|access-date=May 15, 2021|archive-date=May 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210515012553/https://people.com/music/marilyn-manson-victims-found-healing-through-bonding/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/breaking-brian-warner-the-women-who-refused-to-let-the-marilyn-manson-story-die|title=Breaking Brian Warner: The women who refused to let the Marilyn Manson story die|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|date=May 7, 2021|access-date=May 15, 2021|archive-date=May 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210515012554/https://www.loudersound.com/features/breaking-brian-warner-the-women-who-refused-to-let-the-marilyn-manson-story-die|url-status=live}}</ref> In a letter dated January 21, 2021, California State Senator [[Susan Rubio]] wrote to the director of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] and the [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]], asking them to investigate allegations several women had made against Manson.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9519916/marilyn-manson-fbi-department-of-justice-abuse-investigation-susan-rubio/|title=Sen. Susan Rubio Calls for FBI, Dept. of Justice to Investigate Marilyn Manson|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=February 2, 2021|access-date=February 8, 2021|last=Chan|first=Anna|archive-date=February 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210221100513/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9519916/marilyn-manson-fbi-department-of-justice-abuse-investigation-susan-rubio/|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 1, former [[fiancée]] [[Evan Rachel Wood]] wrote on [[Instagram]] and in a statement to ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', accusing Manson of being abusive during their relationship a decade earlier.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evan Rachel Wood accuses Marilyn Manson of abuse|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-55889002|date=February 1, 2021|website=[[BBC News Online]]|access-date=February 1, 2021|archive-date=February 1, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201181042/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-55889002|url-status=live}}</ref> Four other women simultaneously issued statements also accusing Manson of abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2021/02/he-horrifically-abused-me-for-years-evan-rachel-wood-and-other-women-make-allegations-of-abuse-against-marilyn-manson|title=He 'Horrifically Abused Me for Years': Evan Rachel Wood and Other Women Make Allegations of Abuse Against Marilyn Manson|author=Ryan, Maureen|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=February 1, 2021|access-date=February 25, 2022}}</ref> Wood continued to make [[allegation]]s against Manson and his wife Lindsay Usich on Instagram, claiming that his alleged abuse included [[antisemitism]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/evan-rachel-wood-marilyn-manson-antisemitism-b1798625.html |title=Evan Rachel Wood accuses Marilyn Manson of anti-Semitic abuse during relationship |work=The Independent |last=Nugent |first=Annabel |date=February 6, 2021 |access-date=April 19, 2022}}</ref> and said she filed a report with the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] against Usich for threatening to [[Internet leak|leak]] photographs of Wood dressed in a [[Nazi uniform]] while wearing an [[Adolf Hitler]]-style [[toothbrush moustache]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2021-02-08/marilyn-manson-evan-rachel-wood-police-report-manager|title=Evan Rachel Wood says she filed a police report against Marilyn Manson's wife|author=D'Zurilla, Christie|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 8, 2021|access-date=May 25, 2022}}</ref> A total of sixteen people have made various allegations against Manson on Instagram.<ref name="BB Timeline">{{cite magazine|title=A Timeline of Abuse Allegations Against Marilyn Manson|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9523386/timeline-abuse-allegations-marilyn-manson/|access-date=November 15, 2021|magazine=Billboard|language=en|archive-date=September 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210924124352/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9523386/timeline-abuse-allegations-marilyn-manson/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Hayley|last=Miller|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/marilyn-manson-all-abuse-allegations_n_601ac24ec5b6c2d891a51e8c|title=Marilyn Manson: All The Allegations Of Abuse, Assault We Know So Far|website=[[HuffPost]]|access-date=February 4, 2021|date=February 3, 2021|archive-date=February 4, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210204003013/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/marilyn-manson-all-abuse-allegations_n_601ac24ec5b6c2d891a51e8c|url-status=live}}</ref>

Manson was immediately dropped by distributing record label [[Loma Vista Recordings]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Michallon|first=Clémence|title=Marilyn Manson dropped by record label Loma Vista following abuse allegations|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/marilyn-manson-label-loma-vista-abuse-claims-b1796055.html|date=February 1, 2021|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|access-date=February 1, 2021|archive-date=February 1, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201220843/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/marilyn-manson-label-loma-vista-abuse-claims-b1796055.html|url-status=live}}</ref> his talent agency [[Creative Artists Agency|Creative Artists]],<ref name=CAA>{{cite news|url = https://variety.com/2021/biz/news/caa-marilyn-manson-evan-rachel-wood-abuse-allegation-1234897902/|title = CAA Drops Marilyn Manson Amid Storm Over Evan Rachel Wood Abuse Allegations|work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date = February 2, 2021|access-date = February 2, 2021|last = Arthur|first = Kate|archive-date = February 2, 2021|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210202171758/https://variety.com/2021/biz/news/caa-marilyn-manson-evan-rachel-wood-abuse-allegation-1234897902/|url-status = live}}</ref> and his long-time manager Tony Ciulla.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Grow|first=Kory|title=Marilyn Manson Dropped by Longtime Manager Amid Sexual and Physical Abuse Allegations|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-dropped-manager-1124545/|date=February 5, 2021|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=February 5, 2021|archive-date=February 5, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210205213908/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-dropped-manager-1124545/|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also removed from future episodes of TV series ''[[American Gods (TV series)|American Gods]]'' and ''[[Creepshow (TV series)|Creepshow]]'', in which he was scheduled to appear.<ref name="BB Timeline"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/marilyn-manson-to-be-edited-out-of-tv-series-american-gods-creepshow-following-abuse-claims-22840682|title=Marilyn Manson to be edited out of TV series American Gods, Creepshow following abuse claims|first=Kate|last=Brayden|work=[[Hot Press]]|date=February 3, 2021|access-date=February 4, 2021|archive-date=February 4, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210204203351/https://www.hotpress.com/music/marilyn-manson-to-be-edited-out-of-tv-series-american-gods-creepshow-following-abuse-claims-22840682|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 2, Manson issued a statement via Instagram, saying, "Obviously, my art and my life have long been magnets for controversy, but these recent claims about me are horrible distortions of reality. My intimate relationships have always been entirely consensual with like-minded partners", and claimed the accusers were "misrepresenting the past".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2021/02/02/entertainment/marilyn-manson-abuse-dropped-record-label/index.html|title=Marilyn Manson posts statement following abuse allegations|author=Melas, Chloe|work=[[CNN]]|date=February 2, 2021|access-date=August 22, 2021|archive-date=August 22, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210822232602/https://edition.cnn.com/2021/02/02/entertainment/marilyn-manson-abuse-dropped-record-label/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> His former wife Dita Von Teese stated that "the details made public do not match my personal experience during our 7 years together as a couple."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Childers |first1=Chad |title=Marilyn Manson's Ex-Wife Dita Von Teese Issues Statement on Abuse Allegations |url=https://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-ex-wife-dita-von-teese-statement-abuse-allegations/ |website=Loudwire |date=February 4, 2021 |access-date=August 25, 2021 |archive-date=May 1, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210501012045/https://loudwire.com/marilyn-manson-ex-wife-dita-von-teese-statement-abuse-allegations/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Former girlfriend Rose McGowan said that Manson was not abusive during their relationship but that her experience had "no bearing on whether he was like that with others before or after".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rose-mcgowan-marilyn-manson-abuse-allegations-1122681/|title=Rose McGowan Says She's 'Proud' of Marilyn Manson accusers|first=Jon|last=Blistein|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 2, 2021|access-date=August 29, 2021|archive-date=March 7, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210307143122/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rose-mcgowan-marilyn-manson-abuse-allegations-1122681/|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 3, the LAPD performed a "welfare check" at Manson's home after receiving a call from a purported friend who was concerned for his wellbeing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequence.net/2021/02/police-marilyn-manson-house/|title=Police Rush to Marilyn Manson's House for Welfare Check: Report|author=Kaufmann, Spencer|work=[[Consequence (publication)|Consequence]]|date=February 4, 2021|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1234670/marilyn-manson-receives-welfare-check-from-police-amid-abuse-allegations|title=Marilyn Manson Receives Welfare Check From Police Amid Abuse Allegations|author=Schnurr, Samantha|work=[[E! Online]]|date=February 4, 2021|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref> The [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] confirmed on February 19 that they were investigating Manson due to allegations of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/feb/19/marilyn-manson-investigation-alleged-domestic-violence |title=Marilyn Manson under investigation for alleged domestic violence |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=February 19, 2021 |access-date=February 26, 2021 |archive-date=February 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210220093320/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/feb/19/marilyn-manson-investigation-alleged-domestic-violence |url-status=live}}</ref>

Four women filed [[civil lawsuit]]s against Manson in the months that followed Wood's allegations,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2022/mar/18/evan-rachel-wood-marilyn-manson-documentary-phoenix-rising|author=Adrian Horton|date=March 18, 2022|title=Evan Rachel Wood's Marilyn Manson doc shows the messy timeline of healing|work=The Guardian}}</ref> [[Esmé Bianco]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2021/04/marilyn-manson-rape-lawsuit-game-of-thrones-esme-bianco-evan-rachel-wood-1234747662/|title=Marilyn Manson Responds To Rape & Abuse Suit By 'Game Of Thrones' Actress Esmé Bianco|first=Dominic|last=Patten|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 30, 2021|access-date=June 30, 2021|archive-date=June 30, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210630045612/https://deadline.com/2021/04/marilyn-manson-rape-lawsuit-game-of-thrones-esme-bianco-evan-rachel-wood-1234747662/|url-status=live}}</ref>  Ashley Morgan Smithline,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2021/06/30/marilyn-manson-now-facing-four-lawsuits-sexual-assault/7816952002/ |title=Fourth accuser sues Marilyn Manson for sexual assault and human trafficking |last=McClellan |first=Jennifer |work=[[USA Today]] |date=June 30, 2021 |access-date=June 30, 2021}}</ref> Ashley Walters,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henderson|first=Cydney|title=Marilyn Manson's former assistant sues him for sexual assault, battery|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2021/05/18/marilyn-manson-former-assistant-ashley-walter-sues-him-sexual-assault-battery/5154700001/|date=May 18, 2021 |access-date=January 2, 2022|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> and an anonymous woman.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Burke|first1=Minyvonne|last2=Dasrath|first2=Diana|date=May 29, 2021|title=Marilyn Manson's ex-girlfriend accuses him of rape, abuse in lawsuit|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/music/marilyn-manson-s-ex-girlfriend-accuses-him-rape-abuse-lawsuit-n1269093|access-date=January 2, 2022 |work=[[NBC News]]}}</ref> Manson's legal team issued statements denying the allegations.<ref>{{cite news|date=May 1, 2021|title=Game of Thrones actress Esme Bianco sues Marilyn Manson alleging abuse|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2021/05/01/game-thrones-actress-esme-bianco-sues-marilynmanson-alleging/|url-status=live|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210501111714/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2021/05/01/game-thrones-actress-esme-bianco-sues-marilynmanson-alleging/|archive-date=May 1, 2021|access-date=May 3, 2021|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-04-30/marilyn-manson-lawsuit-esme-bianco-sexual-assault-human-trafficking|title='GoT' actress Esmé Bianco sues Marilyn Manson for sexual assault, human trafficking|last=Ylanan|first=Aida|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 30, 2021|access-date=May 2, 2021|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210501000852/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-04-30/marilyn-manson-lawsuit-esme-bianco-sexual-assault-human-trafficking|archive-date=May 1, 2021|url-status=live}}</ref> They filed a motion to dismiss these lawsuits, calling the claims "untrue, meritless" and alleging that several of the accusers "spent months plotting, workshopping, and fine-tuning their stories to turn what were consensual friendships and relationships with Warner from more than a decade ago, into twisted tales that bear no resemblance to reality".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-58010542|title=Marilyn Manson files to dismiss Esme Bianco's sex assault case|author=Savage, Mark|work=BBC|date=July 29, 2021|access-date=July 29, 2021|archive-date=July 29, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210729100519/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-58010542|url-status=live}}</ref> The lawsuit filed by the anonymous woman was initially dismissed because it exceeded the [[statute of limitations]],<ref name="NBC">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/music/judge-dismisses-ex-girlfriend-s-lawsuit-against-marilyn-manson-over-n1279328|title=Judge dismisses ex-girlfriend's lawsuit against Marilyn Manson over statute of limitations|author1=Wong, Wilson Wong|author2=Dasrath, Diana|work=[[NBC News]]|date=September 16, 2021|access-date=September 16, 2021|archive-date=September 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210916132134/https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/music/judge-dismisses-ex-girlfriend-s-lawsuit-against-marilyn-manson-over-n1279328|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/judge-dismisses-lawsuit-accusing-marilyn-manson-of-sexual-assault/|title=Judge Dismisses Lawsuit Accusing Marilyn Manson of Sexual Assault|author=Minsker, Evan|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=September 15, 2021|access-date=September 16, 2021|archive-date=September 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210916032212/https://pitchfork.com/news/judge-dismisses-lawsuit-accusing-marilyn-manson-of-sexual-assault/|url-status=live}}</ref> although an amended complaint was refiled soon after.<ref>{{cite news |last=Legaspi |first=Althea |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-one-sexual-assault-lawsuit-dismissed-1227525/ |title=Woman Accusing Marilyn Manson of Rape, Threatening Life Revives Lawsuit |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=September 23, 2021 |access-date=September 30, 2021 |archive-date=September 27, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210927035030/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-one-sexual-assault-lawsuit-dismissed-1227525/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mims |first=Taylor |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9636081/marilyn-manson-rape-accuser-refiles-complaint-after-judge-dismisses-original-lawsuit/ |title=Marilyn Manson Rape Accuser Refiles Complaint After Judge Dismisses Original Lawsuit |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=September 24, 2021 |access-date=October 4, 2021}}</ref> Manson's legal team also sought to have Bianco's lawsuit dismissed because it exceeded the statute of limitations, although a federal judge denied that motion.<ref name="denies">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2021/10/08/esme-bianco-marilyn-manson-sexual-assault-lawsuit-can-proceed-judge/6049222001/ |title=Judge denies Marilyn Manson's motion to dismiss Esmé Bianco's sexual assault lawsuit |work=[[USA Today]] |date=October 10, 2021 |access-date=October 11, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=August |last2=Exposito |first2=Suzy |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-11-05/marilyn-manson-esme-bianco-sexual-abuse-allegations |title=Marilyn Manson's accusers detail his alleged abuse. 'He's so much worse than his persona' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 5, 2021 |access-date=November 12, 2021}}</ref> Walters's lawsuit was dismissed [[with prejudice]] in May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/losangeles/news/sexual-harassment-suit-against-marilyn-manson-dismissed-by-judge/|title=Sexual harassment suit against Marilyn Manson dismissed by judge|work=[[CBS News]]|date=May 25, 2022|access-date=May 25, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2022/05/26/marilyn-manson-sexual-assault-lawsuit-former-assistant-dismissed/9939748002/|title=Judge dismisses sexual assault lawsuit against Marilyn Manson filed by former assistant|author=Brisco, Elise|work=[[USA Today]]|date=May 26, 2022|access-date=May 26, 2022}}</ref>

Manson filed a lawsuit against Wood and Ashley "Illma" Gore for defamation, intentional infliction of emotional distress, violations of the [[California Comprehensive Computer Data Access and Fraud Act]], as well as the impersonation of an FBI agent and falsifying federal documents.<ref name="Defamation">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marilyn-manson-sues-evan-rachel-wood-defamation-1315320/|title=Marilyn Manson Sues Evan Rachel Wood for Defamation, Distress, Impersonating FBI|author=Grow, Kory|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=March 2, 2022|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref> In the suit, it is alleged that Wood and Gore spent three years contacting his former girlfriends and provided "checklists and scripts" to prospective accusers in order to corroborate Wood's claims,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2022-03-02/marilyn-manson-sues-evan-rachel-wood-fraud-lawsuit|title=Marilyn Manson accuses ex Evan Rachel Wood of fraud, conspiracy in wild lawsuit|author=Saad, Nadine|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 2, 2022|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/marilyn-manson-sues-evan-rachel-wood-for-defamation-1848610941|title=Marilyn Manson sues Evan Rachel Wood for defamation|author=Hughes, William|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=March 2, 2022|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref> and that the pair impersonated and falsified documents from an FBI agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2022/mar/02/marilyn-manson-defamation-lawsuit-evan-rachel-wood|title=Marilyn Manson files defamation suit against sexual abuse accuser Evan Rachel Wood|author=Yang, Maya|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=March 2, 2022|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref> The suit additionally claims Gore hacked into Manson's computers and social media, and created fake email accounts to manufacture evidence he had been distributing "illicit pornography".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2022/03/marilyn-manson-lawsuit-evan-rachel-wood-abuse-claims-hbo-documentary-1234968988/|title=Marilyn Manson Sues Evan Rachel Wood Over Alleged "Malicious Falsehood" Of Abuse Claims; 'Westworld' Actress Forged FBI Letter, Suit Claims|author=Patten, Dominic|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 2, 2022|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref> It is also alleged that Gore [[swatting|swatted]] Manson by calling the FBI claiming to be a friend concerned about an "emergency" at his home. As a result of the call, several police officers were dispatched to his property, where "there was no emergency".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/marilyn-manson-sues-evan-rachel-wood-documentary-not-director-hbo-1684353|title=Marilyn Manson Sues Evan Rachel Wood for Documentary, but Not Director, HBO|author=Slisco, Aila|work=[[Newsday]]|date=March 2, 2022|access-date=April 22, 2022}}</ref> He is seeking a jury trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/marilyn-manson-sues-evan-rachel-wood-saying-actress-cast-him-as-a-rapist-and-abuser-12556404|title=Marilyn Manson sues Evan Rachel Wood, saying actress cast him as a 'rapist and abuser'|author=Minelle, Bethany|work=[[Sky News]]|date=March 2, 2022|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/marilyn-manson-former-lover-says-evan-rachel-wood-recruit-her-lawsuit-1684409|title=Marilyn Manson's Ex-Lover Says Evan Rachel Wood's Accusers Group Tried to Recruit Her|author=Nolan, Emma|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 3, 2022|access-date=March 3, 2022}}</ref>

The LACSD presented the findings of their 19-month investigation of the sexual assault allegations made against Manson to California [[district attorney]] [[George Gascón]] in September 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-09-20/marilyn-manson-sexual-abuse-investigation-george-gascon|title=Marilyn Manson sexual abuse investigation turned over to Los Angeles County D.A.|author=Winton, Richard|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 20, 2022|access-date=October 8, 2022}}</ref> Gascón called the file "partial" and said more evidence was needed in order to file charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/la-marilyn-manson-sexual-assault-allegations/2988606/|title=Marilyn Manson Sexual Assault Allegations Submitted to DA's Office|work=[[NBC]]|date=September 20, 2022|access-date=October 8, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/prosecutors-more-evidence-needed-charges-marilyn-manson-investigation/|title=Prosecutors say more evidence needed before abuse charges can be brought against Marilyn Manson|author=Schaffner, Lauryn|work=[[Loudwire]]|date=September 21, 2022|access-date=October 8, 2022}}</ref>

